DO  -  10.2139/ssrn.5698224
AB  -  Background: Friedreich’s Ataxia (FRDA) is a chronic, progressive neurodegenerative condition marked by cardiac and skeletal muscle involvement. Low cardiovascular fitness is common among individuals living with FRDA. We tested the effect of exercise and NAD+ precursor supplementation with nicotinamide riboside (NR) on aerobic capacity in FRDA. Methods: This Phase 2, single‐site, randomized, 2x2 factorial clinical trial, recruited individuals (10‐40 years) with FRDA, ejection fraction ≥45%, and able to exercise. Randomization was age‐stratified (<18y vs. ≥18y) to one of four groups: placebo + attention control (weekly phone calls), NR + attention control, placebo + exercise, NR + exercise. In‐home exercise included 3 aerobic and 2 resistance training sessions weekly, overseen via telephone. Dosing of NR/placebo was 300mg (24‐<48kg), 600 mg (48kg‐<72kg), or 900mg (≥72kg) orally daily. Treatment duration was 12 weeks. The primary outcome was change in peak VO2 (L/min) during a cardiopulmonary exercise test at 12 weeks vs. baseline. Analyses were by intention‐to‐treat. Adverse events (AEs) were recorded systematically. The trial was registered with ClinicalTrials.gov (NCT04192136). Findings: Between Sep 3, 2020, and Nov 11, 2024, 66 eligible individuals were randomized. Thirty‐three (50%) were children; 37 (55%) were male. All completed the study. The mean difference in peak VO2 for the NR + exercise versus the placebo plus attention control group, adjusting for age, sex, and baseline peak VO2, was 0.21 L/min (95% CI: 0.05, 0.36; p=0.029); the effect of NR + exercise was nominally but not statistically greater than placebo + exercise. Age impacted outcomes (p=0.011 for interaction); children responded to NR alone, and adults to exercise with or without NR. There were no serious AEs. Interpretation: NR plus exercise for 12 weeks was safe and increased cardiovascular fitness in children and adults with FRDA. Adding NR to exercise could be considered as part of a comprehensive treatment approach. 
