DO  -  10.1093/humrep/deaf097.217
AB  -  Study question: Can supplementation of Nicotinamide mononucleotide in young infertile women with diminished ovarian reserve reverse the declining oocyte quality and improve fertility outcome? Summary answer: Pretreatment with Nicotinamide mononucleotide increases ovarian response to stimulation and improves oocyte &amp; embryo quality in young low prognosis women with diminished ovarian reserve What is known already: Management of women with diminished ovarian reserve( DOR) to stimulation is one of the major challenges in reproductive medicine . The primary cause of DOR in young women remain elusive and oxidative stress and mitochondrial dysfunction are among the most investigated possible mechanism.Recent advancement of Sirtuin, a silent information regulator protein have a major role in female meiosis and reproductive longivity and a major determinant influencing ovarian aging and gamate quality. Nicotinamide mononucleotide( NMN),a sirtuin activator and a key NAD+ intermediate can reverse defect in mitochondrial homeostasis, reactive oxygen species(ROS) production, DNA repair and cell survival due to insufficient NAD. Study design, size, duration: Participants/materials, setting, methods: INCLUSION CRITERIA: Age<35yrs AMH level<1ng/ml AFC<5EXCLUSION CRITERIA: Age ≥35yrs H/O ovarian surgery Uterine malformation Tubal blockage. Primary Objective:To assess high quality follicles generated from one stimulation cycle.Secondary Endpoint: Duration of stimulation Total dose of gonadotrophin Endometrial thickness on the day of HCG trigger Fertilization rate.Follicular monitoring was done from D10‐D18 of menstrual cycle in both groups and hen a mature follicle of>18mm is observed, vascularity of follicle and endometrium is checked and HCG trigger was given. Luteal phase support was given after trigger. Main results and the role of chance: The improvement in follicles size after treatment completion in gr A(12.02±1.38mm to 20.38±1.46mm) compared to gr B(11.34±1mm to 15.7±1.86mm) were highly statistically significant (p‐value <0.001).After treatment, mean endometrial thickness was 10.02 ± 1.03mm in gr A and 7.74 ± 0.67mm in gr B which is statistically significant( p<0.001).Follicle vascularity was evaluated after the treatment completion and was found higher in treatment group with 77.6 ± 6.94 % (Grade 04) compared to control group with 59±13.61% (Grade 03 ). Treatment group required only 4 doses of FSH injection 75 IU in one cycle whereas control group required 7‐ 9 doses of FSH injection 75 IU.Mean dose of gonadotropins in treatment group was 267 ± 37.99 IU while in control group it was 471 ± 98.07 IU.At the end of the study, treatment group reported 12 pregnancies and 01 abortion while the control group reported 06 pregnancies and 01 abortion. NMN treated group demonstrated a higher fertilization rate with 48% positive pregnancies compared to control group with 24% fertilization rate. Abortion rate is lower in groupA (8.33%) compared to control (16.66). Group A conceived within 3 months of ovulation induction whereas control group took longer time 6‐9 months. Limitations, reasons for caution: The sample size employed in this study might have been insufficient to detect more subtle effect and study duration might not have adequately captured the longterm consequences of NMN intervention. Wider implications of the findings: Pre treatment with NMN in patient with DOR imparts a possible beneficial effect on clinical pregnancy &amp; live birth rates but needs to be confirmed in larger randomised controlled studies. Further work is required to established the optimal length,timing,doses of treatment to evaluate the therapeutic effect of NMN supplementation.
