AB  -  Purpose : Intraocular pressure (IOP) reduction is the only evidence‐based treatmentshown to slow optic nerve degeneration in glaucoma, the leading cause of irreversibleblindness. Despite adequate IOP control, vision loss often progresses. Decreasing nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD) levels may contribute to axon degeneration. The INSIGHT trial aimed to investigate whether augmenting NAD levels through nicotinamide riboside (NR), an NAD precursor, provides neuroprotection for patients with progressing glaucoma. Methods : This is a randomized, double‐blind, placebo‐controlled trial involved patients exhibiting optical coherence tomography (OCT) evidence of progressive retinal nerve fiber layer (RNFL) or ganglion cell inner plexiform layer thinning. Participants were recruited from three Hong Kong ophthalmology clinics and were randomly assigned (1:1) to receive oral NR 300mg/day or placebo. Follow‐up assessments included OCT imaging and visual field testing every two months over 24 months. The primary outcome measure was the rate of RNFL thinning. The trial was registered with Chinese Clinical Trial Registry (1900021998). Results : Between March 9, 2020, and March 8, 2021, 118 patients were assigned to receive NR (n=61) or placebo (n=57). No statistically significant differences were observed between groups in the rates of RNFL thickness change (mean difference: 0.02μm/year, 95% CI: ‐0.63‐0.66μm/year) or visual field index (VFI) (mean difference: 0.46%/year, 95% CI: ‐0.77‐1.69%/year). IOP levels remained similar throughout the trial (mean between‐group difference: ‐0.56mmHg, 95% CI: ‐1.6‐0.5mmHg). Prespecified subgroup analysis revealed that older patients receiving NR experienced increased rates of RNFL thinning and VFI decline, with NR associated with faster rates of RNFL thinning by 0.03 μm/year (95% CI: 0.01‐0.05 μm/year) and VFI decline by 0.04%/year (95% CI: 0.003‐0.07%/year) for each additional year of age. Conclusions : Oral NR did not slow glaucoma progression and may accelerate optic nerve degeneration in elderly patients, even at the recommended dosage. .
