AB  -  Background: There are currently no curative treatments for dementia, and rates of cognitive impairment continue to rise as the population ages. Mild cognitive impairment (MCI) is an area of interest for treatment development, as intervening at this stage may prevent progression to dementia. Preclinical studies in model organisms suggest that maintaining levels of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+) is a promising approach to sustain cognitive performance and overall health. NAD+ is a coenzyme that has proven to enhance lifespan and healthspan in model organisms. Recent clinical studies have demonstrated that supplementation with nicotinamide riboside (NR), an NAD+ precursor, is well tolerated in young and older adults and successfully increases blood NAD+ levels. Here, we report the baseline characteristics of a larger clinical trial to determine whether NR administration affects cognition or cerebral blood flow in older adults with MCI. Methods: A 10‐week double blind, randomized, placebocontrolled trial was conducted on participants age 65+ with MCI and with normal cognition. Study outcomes include changes in: cognitive and physical function, NAD+ metabolites, standard blood chemistries, fMRI imaging, and epigenetics. Results: 29 participants were enrolled with 26 completing the trial. Dropouts had no trial related adverse events. Baseline characteristics of all enrolled provided in table. Conclusions: Baseline characteristics of participants in the NR/ Placebo groups were not significantly different. Analysis is pending for all outcome measures. This was the first clinical trial of NAD+ in participants with cognitive impairment. Positive findings from this trial may to larger trials of using NAD+ supplementation in older adults with cognitive impairment.
UR  -  https://www.cochranelibrary.com/central/doi/10.1002/central/CN-02230105/full
