AB  -  Background: Glaucoma, the leading cause of irreversible blindness, is characterized by optic nerve degeneration. While intraocular pressure (IOP) reduction is the only proven treatment to slow this degeneration, many patients continue to lose vision despite adequate IOP control. Reduced nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD) levels have been implicated in axonal degeneration, a hallmark of glaucoma progression. This study investigated whether supplementation with nicotinamide riboside (NR), an NAD precursor, provides neuroprotection in patients with progressing glaucoma.Methods: This randomized, double‐blind, placebo‐controlled trial enrolled patients with progressing glaucoma, defined by optical coherence tomography (OCT)‐confirmed progressive retinal nerve fiber layer (RNFL) or ganglion cell inner plexiform layer thinning. Participants from three university‐affiliated eye clinics in Hong Kong were randomized (1:1) to receive NR 300 mg/day or placebo for 24 months. Follow‐up assessments included OCT imaging and visual field testing at 2‐month intervals. The primary outcome was the rate of RNFL thinning. The trial was registered with the Chinese Clinical Trial Registry (1900021998).Findings: Between March 9, 2020, and March 8, 2021, 118 patients were randomized to receive NR (n=61) or placebo (n=57). There were no statistically significant differences between groups in the rates of RNFL thinning (mean difference: 0.038µm/year, 95% CI: ‐0.581–0.656µm/year) or visual field index (VFI) decline (mean difference: 0.471%/year, 95% CI: ‐0.815–1.757%/year). IOP levels remained comparable between groups throughout the trial (mean difference: ‐0.7mmHg, 95% CI: ‐1.7‐0.4mmHg). Prespecified subgroup analysis revealed that older patients receiving NR, but not placebo, experienced faster RNFL thinning and VFI decline. For each additional year of age, these rates accelerated by 0.027µm/year (95% CI: 0.005–0.048µm/year) and 0.036%/year (95% CI: 0.002–0.070%/year), respectively.Interpretation: NR supplementation did not slow glaucoma progression and may accelerate optic nerve degeneration in elderly patients, even at the over‐the‐counter dosage.
UR  -  https://www.cochranelibrary.com/central/doi/10.1002/central/CN-02854625/full
