DO  -  10.1016/j.fertnstert.2024.08.101
AB  -  OBJECTIVE: The decline in oocyte quality is the primary factor contributing to reduced fertility in women of advanced maternal age (AMA). Previous research has highlighted an increased prevalence of abnormal mitochondria and reduced nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+) levels in oocytes from AMA women. Restoring and enhancing oocyte NAD+ levels could be a promising intervention. This study aims to explore the impact of nicotinamide mononucleotide (NMN) supplementation, an NAD+ precursor, during in vitro maturation (IVM) on oocyte quality and embryo development in AMA women. MATERIALS AND METHODS: A total of 164 immature oocytes from women aged ≥38 years undergoing controlled ovarian hyperstimulation cycles were collected. These oocytes were randomly allocated to either the AMA group (72 oocytes) or the AMA + 10 μmol/L NMN group (92 oocytes) and subjected to IVM for 48 hours. Following IVM, intracytoplasmic sperm injection and embryo culture were conducted. The mitochondrial ultrastructure in the oocytes was examined using transmission electron microscopy (TEM) (n = 5). Mitochondrial activity and membrane potential were assessed using MitoTracker and Tetramethylrhodamine ethyl ester (TMRE) probes (n = 10). Single‐cell RNA transcriptome sequencing was performed and analyzed (n = 5). RESULTS: The results indicated that NMN supplementation did not significantly enhance the rates of in vitro maturation, normal fertilization, and cleavage of immature oocytes from AMA women. However, there were substantial improvements in effective embryos (53.3% vs. 29.4%), high‐quality embryos (31.7% vs. 8.8%), blastocyst formation (31.2% vs. 6.2%), and high‐quality blastocysts (70.0% vs. 23.5%) in the AMA + NMN group (all P < 0.05). TEM results revealed an increase in the number of mitochondria with intact inner and outer membranes and clear cristae in the AMA + NMN oocytes compared to the AMA group (P < 0.05). Fluorescence signal quantification analysis demonstrated significantly higher TMRE (P < 0.05) and MitoTracker (P < 0.05) fluorescence intensities in the AMA + NMN group. Single‐cell transcriptome analysis identified 277 significantly upregulated genes and 183 significantly downregulated genes in the AMA + NMN group compared to the AMA group. Gene Ontology (GO) analysis of differentially expressed genes showed significant enrichment in mitochondrial‐related terms such as "positive regulation of protein targeting to mitochondrion" and "mitochondrial matrix." Real‐time quantitative PCR results confirmed the upregulation of oxidative phosphorylation genes (ATP6V1D, ATP5MC1, PPA1, NDUFC1, CYC1, NDUFA12, and NDUFB3) in IVM oocytes of the Aged + NMN group, validating the RNA‐seq data accuracy. CONCLUSIONS: In AMA women, the inclusion of NMN during the IVM process significantly enhanced the developmental potential of IVM oocytes, particularly in terms of blastocyst formation rate and high‐quality blastocyst rate. NMN supplementation may boost oocyte developmental potential by improving mitochondrial morphology and function. IMPACT STATEMENT: This study presents a novel approach to enhancing oocyte quality and embryo development in AMA women through NMN supplementation during IVM. SUPPORT: This study was supported by grants from the Ministry of Science and Technology of China (2018YFC1005001), and National Natural Science Foundation of China (31601197). REFERENCES: LU X, LIU Y, XU J, et al. Mitochondrial dysfunction in cumulus cells is related to decreased reproductive capacity in advanced‐age women[J]. Fertil Steril, 2022. 118(2): p. 393‐404. Bertoldo MJ, Listijono DR, et al. NAD+ Repletion Rescues Female Fertility during Reproductive Aging. Cell Rep. 2020;30(6):1670‐1681.e7.
