DO  -  10.1016/S0016-5085(24)03715-6
AB  -  Background: Intermittent reduced calorie diets (IRCD) substantially reduce daily caloric consumption for short periods and show health benefits similar to standard fasting. In an abstract describing our prespecified interim analysis, our group demonstrated a trend towards clinical response following IRCD in patients with Crohn's disease (CD). Given these findings, we aimed to delineate microbiome/metabolome profiles that may be underlying these clinical results. Methods: We analyzed stool samples from a subset of 16 adult patients with mild to moderate CD (CD Activity Index (CDAI) score (151‐450)) who completed three cycles of a 5‐day IRCD over three consecutive months as part of an open‐label, randomized, controlled‐clinical trial (NCT04147585). Stool samples were collected at baseline, post‐IRCD (3 diet cycles), and after a 2‐month washout. Responders were defined as patients with CDAI≤150 or decrease by ≥100 points from baseline to post‐IRCD. We utilized untargeted metabolome and 16S rRNA sequencing to analyze changes in metabolites and gut microbial composition in stool samples of responders (n=11) compared to non‐responders (n=5). Results: Untargeted metabolome clustered 25 modules into three groups, each exhibiting unique patterns in response to IRCD intervention (Fig.A). We then identified 11 significant KEGG pathways between baseline and Post‐IRCD, most notably enriched arachidonic acid (AA) and steroid hormone biosynthesis pathways (FDR<0.05) (Fig.B). In the AA pathway, pro‐inflammatory leukotriene B4 and prostaglandin H2 both decreased in post‐IRCD, but only prostaglandin H2 rebounded after washout (p<0.05), indicating a potential diet‐induced time sensitive effect (Fig.C). Testosterone and estradiol showed increased trend in all patients from baseline to post‐IRCD (Fig.D). Compared to NR, responders (RS) had lower levels of sex hormone and higher cholesterol levels (p<0.05) at baseline. Hence, RS showed a more significant change at Post‐IRCD, especially estrodial (p<0.05). RS (vs. NR) also had higher Firmicutes levels at baseline (Fig.E‐F). While microbial diversity remained largely unchanged post‐IRCD, a more detailed analysis revealed responders had greater changes of alpha and beta diversity from the baseline in RS vs. NR (Fig.G). Conclusions: IRCD reduced proinflammatory prostaglandin and leukotriene levels combined with increased anti‐inflammatory sex hormone levels, suggesting IRCD may mediate its beneficial effect on CD at a metabolic level. This dietary approach may be more effective in individuals with a lower concentration of sex hormones and/or higher Firmicutes abundance in the gut microbiome, indicating a potential means to identify patients who may respond to the IRCD (and potentially other diets) a priori. The microbial and metabolomic profiling may discern personalized signatures predicting responsiveness to IRCD. [figure presented]
