AB  -  Rationale: Sarcopenia, a loss of skeletal muscle mass, and malnutrition are common in elderly patients and are harbinger of poor outcome, especially in rehabilitation settings. The aim of this study is to assess the effect of rehabititation associated with or not with BCAA enriched nutritional support in elderly patients on muscle mass, nutritional status and physical performance. Methods: This prospective randomized study (UMIN Clinical Trials Registry: UMIN000006238) enrolled 39 elderly patients in an inpatient convalescent rehabilitation ward in Japan. All were underwent a standardized protocol of a few months of inpatient rehabilitation. They were randomly assigned into two groups, according to the adoption (N/R: n = 20) or not (R: n = 19) of the additional BCAA enriched nutritional supplementation. The outcome measures of interest for the present analyses were anthropometric measurements (including body mass index and calf circumference [CC]), strength markers (including grip strength), some haematological markers and several physical activity tests. Results: Baseline characteristics data did not differ significantly between the two groups. Patients in N/R group had significant improvements for the outcome measures compared to those in R group, including CC (changes from baseline: 1.11±1.55[SD], 0.43±0.68, p < 0.05), serum albumin (0.32±0.20, 0.14±0.36, p < 0.05) and cholinesterase level (35.15±76.00, 16.48±31.62, p < 0.05). There was no significant effect for physical performance tests. Conclusion: The results of this study suggest that BCAA enriched nutritional support may be effective at improving muscle mass and nutritional status in rehabilitation settings.
