AB  -  Rationale: Changes in hormone levels throughout a woman's life cycle significantly influence serum lipid concentration. The variations in serum lipid profile can lead to a higher probability of developing cardiovascular diseases. The consumption of dietary polar lipids (PLs) can influence lipid profile and, in turn, cardiovascular health. This research aimed to ascertain the impact of fermented buttermilk consumption on the serum lipid profile in perimenopausal women. Methods: The randomized preliminary clinical trial was realized included eight perimenopausal women with a mean age of 49.0 years (intervention group (n=4): 46.0±2.0 years; control group (n=4): 50.3±1.9 years), mean weight 74.3 ±17.9 kg (intervention group: 68.3±11.3 kg; control group: 80.3±22.9 kg), mean BMI 25.2±5.5 kg/m2 (intervention group: 23.2±3.9 kg/m2; control group (n=4): 27.2±6.7 kg/m2). The intervention group consumed 250 mL (0.32 g PLs) of fermented buttermilk daily for 28 days while maintaining their usual diet and exercise routines. The control group was instructed to make no alterations to their current lifestyle. The enzymatic colour reaction method was used to determine low‐density lipoprotein cholesterol (LDL‐C), high‐density lipoprotein cholesterol (HDL‐C), and triglycerides (TG) levels. Prior to the initiation of the study, approval was obtained from the Ethics Committee of Rīga Stradiņš University (Nr. 2‐PĒK‐4/513/2022). Results: After 28 days of the trial, the intervention group showed decreased LDL‐C and increased HDL‐C levels. Conversely, there was an increase in LDL‐C level and a decrease in HDL‐C level in the control group. Both groups showed a decrease in TG levels (table 1). [Formula presented] Conclusion: The preliminary research suggests that the intake of fermented buttermilk could potentially enhance serum lipid levels in perimenopausal women with moderately elevated level of LDL‐C. References: Dong J., Yang S., Zhuang Q. et al. (2021). The Associations of Lipid Profiles With Cardiovascular Diseases and Death in a 10‐Year Prospective Cohort Study. Frontiers in Cardiovascular Medicine, 8, 745539. https://doi.org/10.3389/fcvm.2021.745539 Jensen J. T., Addis I. B., Hennebold J. D. et al. (2017). Ovarian Lipid Metabolism Modulates Circulating Lipids in Premenopausal Women. The Journal of Clinical Endocrinology and Metabolism, 102(9), 3138–3145. https://doi.org/10.1210/jc.2016‐3456 Kleiblová P., Springer D., Haluzík M (2006). The influence of hormonal changes during menstrual cycle on serum adiponectin concentrations in healthy women. Physiological Research, 55(6), 661–666. https://doi.org/10.33549/physiolres.930977 Mumford S., Dasharathy S., Pollack A. Z., et al. (2011). Variations in lipid levels according to menstrual cycle phase: Clinical implications. Clinical Lipidology, 6(2), 225–234. https://doi.org/10.2217/clp.11.9 Acknowledgments. The research was funded by the "Strengthening Research Capacity in the Latvia University of Life Sciences and Technologies" program, the project titled "The study of buttermilk polar lipids" Disclosure of Interest: None declared
