AB  -  Nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+) is a classical enzyme that plays a pivotal role in cellular redox metabolism. Recent studies have revealed the importance of NAD+ biology in a wide variety of biological processes, such as metabolism, aging, circadian rhythm, and inflammation. Data obtained from our recent studies suggest that defective NAD+ biosynthesis in key metabolic organs, such as adipose tissue, liver, and intestine, is critically involved in the pathogenesis of impaired insulin secretion, insulin resistance, and diabetes. In addition, we reported that nicotinamide mononucleotide (NMN), a key NAD+ intermediate, stimulates NAD+ biosynthesis and treats various metabolic complications associated with obesity and aging. More recently, we conducted a randomized, placebocontrolled, double‐blind trial in postmenopausal women with prediabetes who were overweight or obese and found that NMN supplementation increases muscle insulin signaling (AKT and mTOR) and insulin sensitivity (insulin‐stimulated glucose disposal). These findings indicate high translational potential of NAD+ biology as therapeutics of metabolic diseases. Indeed, there has been also considerable progress in understanding the importance of NAD+ biology in the field of neuroscience research. Data obtained from recent studies conducted in rodent models have demonstrated the therapeutic potential of NAD+ biology in various neurodegenerative diseases, such as Alzheimer's disease and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS), and peripheral neuropathy. This session aims to highlight recent advances in basic and clinical NAD+ biology research and provide insight into the pathophysiological significance and therapeutic potential of NAD+ metabolism in diabetic neuropathy.
