AB  -  The aim of the study was to study the clinical and genotypic features of nephropathy in ischemic stroke (IS) Materials and methods. We examined: 31 patients with metabolic syndrome with nephropathy. All groups are randomized and the patients were aged 40 to 75 years. From the study, individuals with primary kidney lesions and severe diseases of the cardiovascular and endocrine system are excluded. A comprehensive examination including clinical follow‐up was carried out, the clinical examination included: examination (collection of data on the condition of internal organs, measurement of blood pressure, determination of body mass index, neuro‐vegetative manifestations: psychoemotional disorders) laboratory methods of analysis. Results. The results of the study showed that the genealogical analysis of nephropathy in IS revealed a high proportion of IS and nephropathy in families. The risk of developing the disease was higher in cases when the father or mother of a proband suffered a nephropathy. To determine the genotype of patients with nephropathy with AI, a mathematical analysis of the relationships between the characteristics characterizing their genotype was carried out. Direct close connection in patients with AI with Nephropathy was detected between the blood groups 0 (I), and Hpl‐1 (r=+0.79), and between this phenotype of the blood group and CpD (r=+0.53). Also, a direct high correlation was found between blood groups 0 (I), haptoglobin 1‐1, and Cp D and indices of dermatoglyphics (r=+0.95); which indicated the interdependence between these signs, characterizing the genotype of IS patients with nephropathy. Conclusions. Establishment of the genotype (blood group 0 (I), Nr 1‐1, C D D) of patients, clinical and laboratory indicators, genealogical studies, dermatoglyphics indicators allows to isolate a group of patients with high risk nephropathy for nephropathy forecasting in patients with IS.
