AB  -  Background: Despite treatment with endocrine therapy (ET), disease progression eventually occurs in most patients with hormone receptorpositive (HR+) advanced breast cancer (ABC). Inhibition of cyclindependent kinase (CDK) 4/6 blocks cell proliferation in ET‐resistant cells and may delay ET resistance in the clinic. The Phase 3, randomized, double‐blind, international MONALEESA‐2 study is evaluating the efficacy and safety of ribociclib (an oral, selective CDK4/6 inhibitor) + letrozole in patients with HR+, human epidermal growth factor receptor 2‐negative (HER2‐) ABC who have received no prior systemic therapy for advanced disease. Material and Methods: Postmenopausal women (N = 668) with HR+, HER2‐ ABC were randomized (1:1) to receive ribociclib (600 mg/day on Days 1‐21 of each 28‐day cycle) + letrozole (2.5 mg/day continuously) or placebo + letrozole, stratified by the presence of liver and/or lung metastases. Prior systemic therapy for ABC and prior CDK4/6 inhibitors were prohibited. Primary endpoint: investigator‐assessed progressionfree survival (PFS); key secondary endpoint: overall survival (OS). Other endpoints included safety and pharmacokinetics. Drug plasma concentrations were assayed from a subset of patients (n = 73, ribociclib + letrozole arm; n = 85, placebo + letrozole arm) at pre‐dose (Cmin) and 2 h post‐dose (C2h) on Cycle 1 Day 15 using validated LC‐MS/MS methods. Results: The study met its primary objective: at the interim analysis (data cut‐off Jan 29, 2016), PFS was significantly improved in the ribociclib arm, with a hazard ratio of 0.556 (95% confidence interval [CI]: 0.429‐0.720; p = 0.00000329). Median PFS was not reached (NR) in the ribociclib + letrozole arm (95% CI: 19.3‐NR) vs 14.7 months in the placebo + letrozole arm (95% CI: 13.0‐16.5). OS data were immature at data cut‐off. Common Grade 3/4 adverse events (≥5% of patients; ribociclib + letrozole vs placebo + letrozole) were neutropenia (59% vs 1%), leukopenia (21% vs 1%), hypertension (10% vs 11%), elevated alanine aminotransferase (9% vs 1%), lymphopenia (7% vs 1%), and elevated aspartate aminotransferase (6% vs 1%). Exposure to letrozole was similar in both arms (Cmin geometric mean ratio [GMR] 0.932 [90% CI: 0.815‐1.07]; C2h GMR 0.899 [90% CI: 0.815‐0.992]). Plasma concentration of ribociclib (geometric mean [CV%]: Cmin 687 ng/mL [69.8]; C2h 1830 ng/mL [40.0]) was within the range observed for the same dose of single‐agent ribociclib. Conclusions: Ribociclib + letrozole significantly prolonged PFS vs placebo + letrozole during first‐line treatment of postmenopausal women with HR+, HER2‐ ABC. The combination of ribociclib + letrozole was well tolerated with no apparent drug‐drug interaction observed between ribociclib and letrozole.
