AB  -  Background/Aims Bulevirtide (BLV) is a novel entry inhibitor of hepatitis delta virus (HDV). In clinical studies, virologic responders (VR) to HDV therapy are defined as patients who achieve a ≥2log10 IU/mL decline in HDV RNA from baseline (BL) or undetectable level (<LLOQ, target not detected). This analysis aimed to evaluate the efficacy of continued BLV monotherapy in those who were partial‐responders (PR) or non‐responders (NR) after 24 weeks (W) of treatment in MYR301 study. Methods MYR301 is an ongoing, open‐label, randomized Phase 3 study evaluating 3 cohort: BLV 2 mg (Arm B) and BLV 10 mg (Arm C) for 144 W, and a delayed treatment arm (Arm A). Results from patients on treatment at 96 W from Arms B + C were included in this analysis. NR and PR were defined as HDV RNA declined <1log10 IU/mL and ≥1 but <2log10 IU/mL from BL, respectively. Rates of participants achieving biochemical response (alanine aminotransferase [ALT] within normal limits [WNL]) were compared between NR, PR, and VR. Results Patients with chronic hepatitis delta (CHD) (N = 94) were included (47 BLV 2 mg; 47 BLV 10 mg). BL characteristics were similar between study arms. At W24, 58 (62%) participants were VR, 22 were PR, and 14 were NR (Table).Of 14 NR at W24, 6 became VR by W96, and 3 became PR, with 5 remaining NR. At W96, ALT had declined by >50% from baseline in 5 of 6 NR (1 achieved ALT WNL). Many patients who were PR (18 of 24; 75%) or NR (6 of 14; 43%) to BLV at W24 achieved VR by W96, with ALT improvements evident in all groups, including NR. Conclusion These results provide evidence for continuing BLV therapy despite early suboptimal virologic responses in CHD patients. (Table Presented).
