DO  -  10.1002/ana.23771
AB  -  Objective: To assess adiponectin (ADP) and its oligomers in women with episodic migraine (EM) before and after treatment of an acute migraine attack. Background: Epidemiological data has demonstrated an association between migraine &amp; body composition in those of reproductive age. Adipokines (eg. adiponectin) are cytokines secreted predominantly from fat cells. Total‐adiponectin (T‐ADP) is comprised of low (LMW), middle (MMW) &amp; high molecular weight (HMW) oligomers. While the HMW &amp; MMW‐ADP oligomers have been implicated in pro‐inflammatory processes, LMW‐ADP has been implicated in anti‐inflammatory processes. Methods: This is an ongoing, double‐blind, placebo controlled, ictal evaluation (pre &amp; post treatment) of serum ADP levels in EM participants recruited from 3 headache centers. Inclusion criteria included: female sex, age >18, &amp; 2‐12 headaches/month. Exclusion criteria included: metabolic, cardiac, inflammatory, infectious, and autoimmune disorders, pain other than migraine &amp; change of migraine prophylactic medications within a month of the study. Serum levels of adiponectin and its oligomers were drawn: 1) within 4 hours of onset of moderate to severe pain and 2) after treatment with sumatriptan/naproxen sodium vs placebo at: 30 min, 60 min &amp; 120 min. Serum T‐ADP was evaluated by RIA. HMW, MMW &amp; LMW‐ADP were evaluated by EIA. To compare treatment vs placebo for the outcome variables of interest (e.g. T‐ADP) independent &amp; paired t‐tests were completed for grouped &amp; repeated measures data accordingly. Results. A total of 20 female episodic migraineurs were included;11 received sumatriptan/naproxen sodium (suma/ nap) and 9 placebo. No significant differences were identified between groups for demographics, (eg. age, race), headache characteristics (eg. frequency, disability), body composition (BMI, WC), or baseline glucose, insulin, cholesterol, estradiol levels. Eleven participants (6 suma /nap &amp; 5 placebo) were identified as responders (R). Of the total group of responders (All‐R), total adiponectin levels were significantly reduced at 30 min (12.52 ±SD 3.4; p=0.030, 60 min (12.32 ±SD 3.2; p=0.017 and 120 min (12.65 ±SD 3.2; p=0.016) as compared to onset (13.48 ±SD 3.8), Table 1. Total adiponectin levels were not significantly reduced in the total group of non‐responders (All‐NR). Similarly suma/nap‐R showed a significant decline in total adiponectin (Total‐ADP) at 60 and 120 min, while no significant changes were found in the non‐responders, Table 1. In All‐R, LMW‐ADP levels were significantly increased at 60 min (1.80 ±SD 0.5; p=0.05) as compared to onset (1.37 ±SD 0.5). LMW‐ADP levels increased in SN‐R and decreased in both groups of NR, but did not reach significance. Conclusion. Total adiponectin &amp; LMW adiponectin are modulated by acute treatment response in women migraineurs. Total adiponectin levels are decreased, while the LMW‐ADP is increased in responders. Adiponectin &amp; ADP oligomers represent potential novel biomarkers of acute abortive treatment response &amp; potential drug targets in women migraineurs. Larger studies are warranted.
