AB  -  Objectives: This phase III study (NCTNCT05715840) aimed to evaluate the efficacy and safety of enlonstobart (SG001, a fully humanized and high‐affinity anti‐PD‐1 immunoglobulin G4 monoclonal antibody) combined with standard of care therapy (SOC) versus placebo combined with SOC for first‐line treatment of PD‐L1 positive recurrent and/or metastatic cervical cancer (r/mCC). Results from the safety run‐in stage are reported. Methods: Eligible patients were aged 18 years or older with histologically confirmed PD‐L1 positive (CPS ≥1) r/mCC who had not been treated with systemic chemotherapy. Patients received SG001 360 mg + paclitaxel 175 mg/m2 + cisplatin 50 mg/m2/carboplatin AUC 5 ± bevacizumab 15 mg/kg every three weeks until disease progression, intolerable toxicities or other study discontinuation criteria were met. The primary endpoint for the safety run‐in stage was safety, secondary endpoints included efficacy outcomes (investigator assessed objective response rate [ORR], disease control rate [DCR], duration of response [DoR] and time to response [TTR]). Results: Between Feb. 8, 2023, and Aug. 22, 2023, 31 patients were enrolled in the safety run‐in stage and received treatment with SG001 combined with SOC. The median age was 54 years (range: 27–67). ECOG performance status was 0 in 12 patients (38.7 %) and 1 in 19 patients (61.3 %); 26 (83.9 %) patients had squamous cell carcinoma, four (12.9 %) had adenocarcinoma and one (3.2 %) had adenosquamous carcinoma. Twenty (64.5 %) patients had local recurrence and distant metastasis, three (9.7 %) had distant metastasis alone and eight (25.8 %) had local recurrence alone. All 31 patients experienced treatment‐related adverse events (TRAEs), of which 21 (67.7 %) patients experienced grade ≥ 3 TRAEs. The most common (occurring ≥20 %) TRAEs were decreased white blood cell count (25/31, 80.6 %), decreased neutrophil count (21/31, 67.7 %), nausea (19/31, 61.3 %), alopecia (17/31, 54.8 %), anemia (16/31, 51.6 %), vomiting (13/31, 41.9 %), fatigue (13/31, 41.9 %), increased alanine transaminase (ALT) (11/31, 35.5 %), decreased platelet count (11/31, 35.5 %), increased aspartate transaminase (AST) (10/31, 32.3 %), hypertriglyceridemia (9/31, 29.0 %), constipation (9/31, 29.0 %), hypoesthesia (9/31, 29.0 %) and decreased appetite (8/31, 25.8 %). There were no treatment‐emergent adverse events (TEAEs) leading to death or TEAEs leading to drug discontinuation. As of Aug. 30, 2024, after a median follow‐up of 11.8 months, the investigator assessed ORR was 80.6 % (95 % CI 62.5–92.6 %), including five complete responses and 20 partial responses. DCR was 90.3 % (95 % CI 74.3–98.0 %). The median DoR was not reached; the median TTR was 1.38 months (IQR 1.31–2.76). The median PFS was 15.1 months (95 % CI 9.9‐NR). Conclusions: SG001 combined with SOC as first‐line treatment was found to be safe with promising efficacy in patients with r/mCC. These data support the trial's progress to the randomized phase III study, which is actively recruiting.
