AB  -  Objectives: In part 1 of the phase III RUBY trial (NCTNCT03981796), dostarlimab combined with carboplatin‐paclitaxel (Dost+CP) significantly improved progression‐free survival (PFS) and overall survival (OS) in patients with primary advanced or recurrent endometrial cancer (EC), leading to its approval for frontline treatment. Here, we report the updated duration of response (DOR) and safety data from the second interim analysis of the RUBY trial. Methods: Patients were randomized 1:1 to receive Dost+CP or placebo (PBO) + CP Q3W (six cycles) followed by Dost or PBO monotherapy Q6W for up to three years. Primary endpoints were PFS and OS in the overall population and PFS in the mismatch repair deficient/microsatellite instability‐high (dMMR/MSI‐H) population. DOR, based on investigator assessment per RECIST v1.1, was a secondary endpoint for the overall and dMMR/MSI‐H populations. DOR in the mismatch repair proficient/microsatellite stable (MMRp/MSS) population was an exploratory endpoint. The median duration of follow‐up at interim analysis 2 was 37.2 months at the data cutoff (DCO) of Sept. 22, 2023. Results: In total, 494 patients were randomized (245 Dost+CP, 249 PBO + CP). At DCO, 150 patients in the Dost+CP arm and 142 patients in the PBO + CP arm achieved a response. In the overall population, median DOR (mDOR) was 10.6 months (95 % CI 8.2–18.4 months) in the Dost+CP arm and 6.2 months (95 % CI 4.4–6.7 months) in the PBO + CP arm. In the Dost+CP arm, 30.7 % of patients had DOR ≥24 months compared with 12.0 % in the PBO + CP arm. In the dMMR/MSI‐H population, 73.6 % (39/53) of patients in the Dost+CP arm and 61.5 % (40/65) of patients in the PBO + CP arm achieved a response. Median DOR (mDOR) in the Dost+CP arm was not reached (95 % CI 10.1 months‐NR) compared with 5.4 months (95 % CI 3.9–8.1 months) in the PBO + CP arm. In the Dost+CP arm, 53.8 % of patients had DOR ≥24 months compared with 10.0 % in the PBO + CP arm. In the MMRp/MSS population, 57.8 % (111/192) of patients in the Dost+CP arm and 55.4 % (102/184) of patients in the PBO + CP arm achieved a response. mDOR in the Dost+CP arm was 8.6 months (95 % CI 6.9–13.1 months) compared with 6.3 months (95 % CI 4.4–7.1 months) in the PBO + CP arm. In the Dost+CP arm, 22.5 % of patients had DOR ≥24 months compared with 12.7 % in the PBO + CP arm. Few patients experienced immune‐related adverse events (irAEs) after 24 months of treatment in either the Dost+CP or PBO + CP arm. After the 24‐month landmark, for the most common irAEs (experienced by ≥5 % of patients throughout the entire duration of the trial), arthralgia was experienced by two patients; rash and increase in alanine aminotransferase (ALT), each experienced by one patient in the Dost arm; ALT increase was experienced by one patient in the PBO arm. Conclusions: These updated DOR results from RUBY part 1 suggest that patients who achieve response have substantially improved duration of response when treated with Dost+CP compared with PBO + CP, with few anticipated irAEs when treated beyond 24 months. These longer‐term follow‐up data support frontline use of Dost+CP as the standard of care in all patients with primary advanced or recurrent endometrial cancer. [Formula presented]
