AB  -  Aims: This post hoc analysis from C‐axSpAnd (NCT02552212) evaluated whether baseline MRI/C‐reactive protein (CRP) status impacted long‐term (3‐year) clinical responses to certolizumab pegol (CZP). Methods: Adults with active non‐radiographic axial spondyloarthritis (nraxSpA) fulfilling Assessment of SpondyloArthritis international Society (ASAS) classification criteria and objective signs of inflammation (CRP≥10 mg/L [CRP+] and/or evidence of sacroiliitis on MRI [MRI+]) were randomised 1:1 to placebo (PBO):CZP (200 mg every 2 weeks [wks, Q2W]; Wks 0/2/4, 400 mg) for 52 weeks; those enrolled into the safety follow‐up extension (SFE) received open‐label (OL) CZP (200 mg Q2W) for an additional 104 weeks. At Wks 52/156, ASDAS, BASDAI, and the percentage of patients achieving ASDAS major improvement (ASDASMI, C‐axSpAnd primary outcome) and ASAS 40% response (ASAS40) were assessed by MRI/CRP status subgroups. Observed case data reported. Results: 243/317 (76.7%) entered the SFE: 120 CZP‐randomised (36 MRI+/CRP+, 32 MRI‐/CRP+, 52 MRI+/CRP‐); 123 PBOrandomised (30 MRI+/CRP+, 34 MRI‐/CRP+, 59 MRI+/CRP‐; 75/123 switched to OL treatment in the 52‐week double‐blind phase). 206/243 completed the SFE: 102/120 (85.0%) CZP‐randomised; 104/123 (84.6%) PBO‐randomised. Mean ASDAS was similar among CZPrandomised patients between timepoints (MRI+/CRP+: 1.6 at Week 52 vs 1.6 at Week 156; MRI‐/CRP+: 2.1 vs 2.2; MRI+/CRP‐: 1.7 vs 1.6); improved among PBO‐randomised patients (MRI+/CRP+: 2.1 vs 1.8; MRI‐/CRP+: 2.2 vs 1.9; MRI+/CRP‐: 2.0 vs 1.7). ASDAS‐MI: lower percentage among CZP‐randomised patients at Week 156 versus Week 52 across all subgroups; proportion sustained among PBOrandomised patients. Mean BASDAI (Week 52‐Week 156): sustained in CZP‐randomised patients across all subgroups; decreased (indicating clinical improvements) in PBO‐randomised patients, with values aligning with those of the CZP‐randomised. ASAS40 (Week 156 vs Week 52): sustained in CZP‐randomised patients; increased percentage of responders in all PBO‐randomised MRI/CRP subgroups. Conclusion: Across MRI/CRP subgroups, long‐term clinical outcomes achieved after 1 year were generally sustained at 3 years in nr‐axSpA patients with objective signs of inflammation; ASDAS‐MI was numerically highest in the MRI+/CRP+ subgroup.
