AB  -  Background/purpose: This post‐hoc analysis from the C‐axSpAnd study aims to evaluate whether response to certolizumab pegol (CZP) in non‐radiographic axial spondyloarthritis (nr‐axSpA) is impacted by patients' baseline C‐reactive protein (CRP) level. Methods: C‐axSpAnd (NCT02552212) is a 3‐year, phase 3, multicenter study including a completed 52 week double‐blind, placebo‐controlled period.1 Post‐hoc efficacy outcomes are reported for patients randomized to CZP 200 mg every 2 weeks or placebo, stratified by baseline CRP (<5 mg/L, ≥5‐<10 mg/L and ≥10 mg/L). The upper limit of normal of the CRP assay was defined as 10 mg/L by the central laboratory, while the lower limit of quantification (LLoQ) was 4 mg/L. In patients with CRP <LLoQ, a CRP value of 2 mg/L (half the LLoQ) was used to calculate ASDAS. Outcomes reported: ASDAS‐MI, ASAS40, ASAS PR, ASDAS‐CRP, BASDAI, BASFI. Results: 159 patients were randomized to CZP and 158 to placebo (56 and 57, respectively, had baseline CRP <5 mg/L; 19 and 20 had CRP ≥5‐<10 mg/L; 84 and 81 had CRP ≥10 mg/L). Response rates for the primary outcome, ASDAS‐MI, were higher in the CRP ≥10 mg/L and CRP ≥5‐<10 mg/L groups vs the CRP <5 mg/L group (Figure 1A). However, since most patients in the CRP <5 mg/L subgroup had CRP <LLoQ, it is unlikely that ASDAS‐MI could be achieved in these patients because the CRP is one of the main factors in ASDAS derivation. For ASAS40, the main secondary outcome, responses were high in all three subgroups (Figure 1B). Across other efficacy measures, improvements were observed at Week 12 in all CZP‐treated CRP subgroups vs placebo, which were sustained or further improved to Week 52 (Table). Conclusion: Clinically relevant responses were observed in all CRP subgroups treated with CZP, including those with a normal CRP value at baseline.
