DO  -  10.1016/j.nmd.2023.07.247
AB  -  We previously reported results from a phase two clinical trial of the glutathione precursor N‐acetylcysteine (NAC) on oxidative stress and endurance in ambulatory individuals with RYR1‐related myopathies (RYR1‐RM, NCT02362425). The primary endpoint (serum glutathione concentration) was replaced with urine 15‐F2t isoprostane owing to methodological constraints. Here, we utilize new assay technology to re‐evaluate redox balance, pre‐ and post‐NAC treatment in banked snap‐frozen whole blood specimens. Reduced and oxidized glutathione (GSH/GSSG) and nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+/NADH) were quantified using a cyclic enzymatic assay with colorimetric detection. Results from RYR1‐RM patients (N=29) were compared to otherwise healthy controls (N=300). Most participants had GSH and GSSG concentrations within normal limits at baseline (74% and 70%, respectively). In contrast, 74% of participants exhibited systemic NAD+ deficiency. NAD+ deficiency persisted over a 12‐month period and there was no change from baseline in redox measures following six‐month NAC treatment, versus placebo. Based on these observations and reported efficacy of niacin treatment for mitochondrial myopathy, we analyzed the NAD+ content of Ryr1 Y524S soleus muscle and initiated experiments testing whether nicotinamide riboside (NR) can increase cellular NAD+ concentrations and modify mitochondrial respiration in RYR1‐RM patient‐derived primary myotubes. Initial results suggest a dose‐dependent increase in cellular NAD+ content and increased basal and maximal respiration in NR‐treated RYR1‐RM primary myotubes. There was no difference in the NAD+ content of Ryr1 Y524S soleus muscle versus controls. Overall, these results may explain absence of a NAC treatment effect and support further exploration of secondary NAD+ deficiency in RYR1‐RM. Experiments testing NR in vitro are ongoing and if successful could provide rationale for a phase I/II randomized controlled trial.
