AB  -  Aim: Bimekizumab (BKZ) is a monoclonal IgG1 antibody that selectively inhibits interleukin (IL)‐17F in addition to IL‐17A. The objective was to report maintenance of stringent clinical responses through one‐year BKZ treatment in patients with non‐radiographic axial spondyloarthritis (nr‐axSpA) and r‐axSpA. Method: BE MOBILE 1 (NCT03928704; nr‐axSpA)/ 2 (NCT03928743; r‐axSpA): randomisation to BKZ 160 mg every 4 weeks (Q4W) or placebo; Weeks (Wks) 16‐52: all received BKZ 160 mg Q4W. ASAS40 and ASDAS < 2.1 (low disease activity [LDA]) or <1.3 (inactive disease [ID]) responses to Wk52 assessed among BKZ‐randomised Wk16 responders; C‐reactive protein (CRP) normalisation responses (high sensitivity [hs]‐CRP ≤5 mg/L) to Wk52 assessed among BKZ‐randomised with elevated baseline CRP (hs‐CRP >5 mg/L) Wk16 responders. Missing data: non‐responder imputation (NRI): ASAS40, CRP normalisation; multiple imputation (MI): ASDAS. Observed case data, and Wk16/52 responder rates for all BKZ‐randomised patients (NRI/MI) reported. Treatment‐emergent adverse events (TEAEs) to Wk52 reported for all patients receiving ≥1 BKZ dose. Results: In BE MOBILE 1/2, BKZ‐randomised patients: 128/221; BKZ‐randomised with elevated baseline CRP: 40/72. Wk16 ASAS40: 47.7%/44.8% (BE MOBILE 1/2), increasing to Wk52: 60.9%/58.4% (NRI). Of Wk16 ASAS40 responders, 82.0%/83.8% maintained response at Wk52 (NRI). Wk16 ASDAS LDA: 46.1%/44.8% (BE MOBILE 1/2), increasing to Wk52: 61.6%/57.1% (MI). Of Wk16 ASDAS LDA responders, 88.9%/88.4% maintained response at Wk52 (MI). Wk16 ASDAS ID: 18.8%/16.4% (BE MOBILE 1/2), increasing to Wk52: 25.2%/23.4% (MI). Among Wk16 ASDAS ID responders, response maintained by 79.2%/75.1% at Wk24, 85.3%/71.7% at Wk36, and 88.0%/58.7% at Wk52 (MI). Among patients with elevated baseline CRP who reported Wk16 normalisation from BE MOBILE1/2 (57.1%/52.6%), 77.5%/76.4% maintained response at Wk52 (NRI). To Wk52 of BE MOBILE 1 and 2, 183/244 (75.0%) and 249/330 (75.5%) patients reported ≥1 TEAE whilst receiving BKZ, respectively; 9 (3.7%) and 20 (6.1%) reported serious TEAEs. Conclusion: Dual inhibition of IL‐17F and IL‐17A with BKZ provided robust maintenance of stringent clinical responses from Wks16‐52 across axSpA disease spectrum.
