AB  -  Introduction Relapse after the end of the therapy with IFN‐alpha is a common problem and retreatment may be necessary. Therefore, other therapeutic strategies need to be explored, combined therapy with leucocyte IFN‐alpha (Le‐IFN‐alpha) plus Ribavirin (R). There are evidences that this combined therapy increase the possibility of a sustained response. Aim Evaluation of the efficacy of 6 months treatment of a combination therapy with Le‐ IFN‐alpha plus R in patient with biopsy proven chronic hepatitis C, who relapsed at the end of a first cycle of IFN‐alpha 2b or IFN‐alpha linfoblastoid (3 M.U.x3/w for 12 months). Patients and methods Thirty six relapsing patients of both sex (age 20‐60 yrs) were randomised in two arms controlled trial to evaluate the efficacy of Le‐IFN‐alpha alone (3 M.U.x3/w for 6 months: group I), compared with a combination therapy with Le‐IFN‐alpha the same dosage plus R (80 mg/daily) (group II). Treatment groups did not significantly differ concerning age, sex, histology and ALT levels. ALT levels was tested every month, qualitative and quantitative HCV‐ RNA were detected at baseline and at three month after the end of the treatments. Were also performed hepatic biopsies before and after therapy. Results Two patients (group I) discontinued the treatment: one for thyroid dysfunction and the other one for non compliance. Six patients (37,5%) of the group I had a sustained response (SR) (ALT normal and HCV‐RNA negative at follow‐up 6‐12 months), seven (43%) responded to treatment but relapsed again during three months follow‐up. The remaining three patients (18%) were non responders (NR). In the group II eight patients (44%) had SR, five (27,7%) early relapsed and five (27%) were NR. No significant differences were found in HCV‐RNA levels detected in the two groups before the therapy and the liver biopsies performed at baseline. In all responders liver histology was improved. In six of the eight NR patients was detected an initial cirrhosis. Conclusions A retreatment with Le‐IFN alpha of relapsed patients may induce a sustained response in about 40% of patients but there is no statistically significant difference in response and viraemia of we use a combined treatment with R. Several patients (23%) may be refractory to retreatment probably when cirrhosis is detected.
