TI  -  Multicenter, placebo-controlled, double-blind trial of interferon alpha-2b plus ribavirin vs interferon alone for retreatment of non-responders and relapsers with chronic hepatitis c who have failed previous treatment with interferon: a 48 week review
JA  -  Hepatology (Baltimore, Md.)
PY  -  1999
VL  -  30
IS  -  4 (Pt 2)
CC  -  HS-HANDSRCH
CC  -  Hepato-Biliary
SP  -  201A
M3  -  Journal article
AB  -  Ribavirin(RIB)+interferon(INF)is more effective than INF alone in the treatment of chronic hepatitis C(HCV) infection. The optimum duration of treatment is not known nor is the response of the group of non‐responders(NR). This trial was designed to examine HCV RNA concentrations after treatment of NR and relapsers(R) for 24 weeks(wk) with INF+RIB or INF, with 24 week crossover to INF+RIB, for a total of 48 week treatment. An end‐of‐treatment analysis is now being reported. Methods 112 patients, followed at six centers in the Triboro Hepatitis C Study Group, were enrolled. 83 were NR, defined as patients who did not have normal ALT activities at the end of at least a two month course of INF treatment. 29 were R, defined as normal ALT at completion of first treatment who subsequently relapsed to abnormal. All received 3 million units INF, 3 times a week for 48wk and were randomized to receive either RIB(1.0gm or 1.2gm) or placebo every day for the first 24wks. Those who received placebo were crossed over to receive RIB for the second 24wks. HCV RNA was detected by reverse transcription‐polymerase chain reaction(RT‐PCR). Results Subject mean age was 49.7yrs and 42% of subjects had cirrhosis or transition to cirrhosis on liver biopsy; 84% were infected with HCV genotype 1. On an intention‐to‐treat basis, at present time, 96 subjects(72NR and 24R) have data available. After 48wk of treatment with INF+RIB, 5 out of 37(14%)of the NR had undetectable HCV RNA compared to 5 out of 12(42%) of the R. None of the patients who had detectable HCV RNA at 24wk converted to undetectable at 48wk. Overall, if the NR &amp; R are grouped together after 48wk of treatment with INF+RIB, 10 out of 49(20%) had undetectable HCV RNA. In the crossover group, 6 out of 35(17%) of the NR had HCV RNA that was undetectable, compared to 7 out of 12(58%) R at the end of treatment. Overall in this crossover group, 5(3 NR &amp; 2 R) out of 47(11%) converted to undetectable HCV RNA after being crossed over to RIB. When the NR &amp; R in this crossover group are looked at together, 13 out of 47(28%) had undetectable HCV RNA. For NR in both groups(INF+RIB x 48wk and crossover), 11 out of 72(15%) had undetectable HCV RNA, compared with 12 out of 24(50%) R. Side effects were similar in both groups. Conclusion (1) The crossover group compared with the 48wk INF+RIB yielded a similar end of treatment response(28% vs. 20%) in our population of mostly(75%) NR; this difference is not sig. (p=.41). (2) There were no new responders(undetectable HCV RNA) after 48wk of treatment with INF+RIB compared with 24wk, therefore we suggest that if after 24wk of INF+RIB the HCV RNA is detectable then treatment should be stopped. (3) R are much more likely(50%) then NR(15%) to have undetectable HCV RNA after treatment with INF+RIB(p=.004). (4)There is a 15.3% chance(95%CI, 7.88%‐25.7%) that NR will respond to a course of treatment with INF+RIB. (5)In responders, it remains to be seen if a total of 24wk of RIB or 48wk of RIB added to INF will result in a higher sustained response, we await the conclusion of our trial.
