TI  -  Retreatment of IFN/ribavirin non-responder hepatitis C patients: benefit of peg-interferon/ribavirin amantadine
JA  -  Hepatology (Baltimore, Md.)
PY  -  2004
VL  -  40
IS  -  4 Suppl 1
CC  -  HS-HANDSRCH
CC  -  Hepato-Biliary
SP  -  398A
M3  -  Journal article
AB  -  Background and aim: The optimal therapy for chronic hepatitis C patients non‐responders (NR) to a previous treatment course is still an unresolved issue. Since the initial favourable preliminary study on the potential benefit of amantadine for NR, other studies have shown controversial results. The aim of this study was to determine if the addition of amantadine to PEG‐IFN/ribavirin enhanced the sustained virological response (SVR) rate. Methods: 202 patients (101 in each group) were treated within a double blind, comparative, prospective multicenter, randomised trial comparing PEG‐IFN 1.5µg/kg/week and ribavirin 800‐1200mg/day plus either amantadine 200mg/day or placebo for 48 weeks. Inclusion criteria were: elevated ALT, detectable HCV‐RNA, METAVIR score more or equal to A1F1 and less or equal to F3, and no response to IFN/ribavirin combination. Endoints were SVR, ALT normalisation, histological benefit (between baseline and W48), and tolerance. Results: Baseline characteristics : genotype 1: 82%; METAVIR stage F3: 35%; HCV‐RNA>800,000 IU/mL: 70%. Regardless of the treatment group, 24% of previous NR patients achieved a SVR and 39% an end‐of‐treatment response. A 9% increased SVR rate was observed in the triple therapy group (28%) compared to the double therapy group (19%), although this difference was not statistically significant (p=0.19). A more pronounced difference (37%) was observed for genotype 2/3 patients in whom SVR was achieved in 100% and 63% of cases in the triple and double therapy groups, respectively (p=0.20). This trend for a beneficial effect of amantadine was also observed in patients with a low baseline viral load (800,000 IU/mL) in whom SVR rates were 52% and 29%, respectively (p=0.10). Although not significant, a better virological response rate at W24 was also observed in the triple regimen group (44% vs 31%; p=0.07). Biochemical response rate was significantly higher in the triple therapy group at W12 compared to double therapy (63% and 49%, respectively; p=0.049) and at W24 (67% vs 50%; p=0.026). A fibrosis improvement (decrease of at least one METAVIR fibrosis point) was observed in 24% of all patients and a stabilisation in 53%. Early discontinuation occurred in 11% and 8% of the triple and double therapy group, respectively (p>0.05). Conclusion: 1. Retreatment of IFN/ribavirin NR patients should be encouraged since a substantial proportion of them (24%) respond to PEG‐IFN/ribavirin +/‐ amantadine and 77% improve or stabilize their fibrosis score. 2. Triple therapy with the addition of amantadine increases the SVR rate, especially in specific subgroups. This trial is one of the first studies indicating a beneficial effect of amantadine in addition to PEG‐IFN/ribavirin combination therapy in IFN/ribavirin NR patients.
UR  -  https://www.cochranelibrary.com/central/doi/10.1002/central/CN-00506920/full
