AB  -  Background and Aims: We previously showed that modelling infected cells dynamics by ALT and HCV RNA decline during the first 4 weeks warrants an early prediction of treatment outcome and might represent a new tool for fine individualisation of treatment duration. The duration and the efficacy of the model tailored (MT) vs the traditional Guide Line (GL) PegIFNs+RBV therapy are compared in an ongoing randomised controlled trial (EudraCT registration # 2006‐002483‐26). Patients and methods: One hundred consecutive patients stratified according to previous therapy (38 naïve, 62 retreated), HCV genotype (60 G1‐G4 and 40 G2‐G3) and peg‐IFN type (60 2a and 40 2b), were randomised to receive GL or MT schedules. GL pts were treated for 24 weeks if G2‐G3 and for 48 weeks if G1‐G4 applying the week 12 stopping rule in G1 non responders (NR). In MT patients ALT and HCV RNA were measured at day 0‐2‐4‐7‐14‐21‐28 to compute the number of infected cells at the end of therapy (Ieot) and treatment was stopped because of NR at week 6 if Ieot>5000 at GL duration, otherwise tailored to achieve Ieot<250. Results: Ieot could be computed in 42 (84%) MT patients, the remaining 8 pts were switched to the GL schedule but not included in the analysis. Therapy was withdrawn/modified because of side effects in 13 (26%) MT and in 9 (18%) GL pts. Therapy was discontinued at week 6 because of NR in 11 (22%) MT pts and at week 12 in 8 (16%) GL pts. The SVR rate in patients who completed therapy was 83% according to the MT schedule (mean duration 32 weeks, range:13‐56) and 82% according to the GL schedule (mean duration 38 weeks, range:24‐48). Individual treatment durations in SVR pts were: 18‐24‐35‐40‐43‐43‐55 weeks in 7 G1 pts, 17‐20‐21 weeks in 3 G2 pts and 21‐29‐30‐46‐56 weeks in 5 G3 pts. Individual treatment durations in Rel pts were: 20 weeks in the G1 pt, 13 weeks in the G2 pt and 51 weeks in the G3 pt. Conclusions: The prospective application of our model showed for the first time that an accurate definition of treatment duration at the single patient level is feasible in clinical practice and that the treatment duration to achieve SVR is a continuous variable with wide individual differences, related only in part to the HCV genotype. Tailoring treatment to Ieot<250 showed SVR rates comparable to standard treatment (83% vs 82%) with a significant reduction of non‐effective and non appropriate treatments: standard GL schedules lasted longer of 18% in responder patients and 100% in non responders. Optimization of the Ieot threshold after larger studies might further improve the cost‐effectiveness of the model.
