AB  -  Patients with chronic HCV infection and non‐response to previous therapies experience viral elimination in less than 15% after retreatment with pegylated interferon alpha (IFNa) and ribavirin. Consensus interferon (CIFN) is a synthetic type I interferon with increased in vitro antiviral activity. In this prospective and randomised study, it should be assessed whether CIFN might lead to enhanced response rates of patients with chronic hepatitis C. Methods: 95 patients (age 57 years, male 56%, cirrhosis / bridging fibrosis 67%, genotype‐1/6 86%) with detectable HCV‐RNA (Roche Amplicor) and elevated ALT after non‐response (NR) or relapse to previous treatment with IFNa (with our without ribavirin) were included. Patients were randomly assigned to treatment arm 1 (CIFN 27mcg QD for 2 weeks followed by 18mcg QD for 10 weeks, 9mcg QD for 12 weeks and 9mcg tiw for 24 weeks; ribavirin 800mg QD from weeks 3 ‐ 48) or arm 2 (CIFN 18mcg tiw for 12 weeks followed by 9mcg tiw for 36 weeks, ribavirin 800 mg QD from the beginning). All 95 patients received at least one dose of CIFN and were included in the analysis. Results: In the intention‐to‐treat analysis, NR patients treated in arms 1 or 2 exhibited end‐of‐treatment virological response rates (ETR; week 48) of 40% vs. 37% and virological sustained response rates (VSR; after 6 months follow up) of 29% vs. 27%. Normalized ALT levels at end of follow up were found in 34 and 30% of patients treated in arm 1 and 2, respectively. Relapse patients treated in arms 1 and 2 had ETR in 75% and 64%, and VSR in 75% and 41%. Sustained biochemical response rates were 88% and 55% in arms 1 and 2. Therapy was quite well tolerated and had to be discontinued due to side effects in 7 and 6% of patients treated in arms 1 and 2, CIFN dose reductions were necessary in 26% and 6% in arms 1 and 2, and one patient in arm 2 had his riba dose reduced. Conclusions: CIFN / riba treatment of patients non‐responsive to previous therapies induced high sustained virological response rates, whereas relapsers could very sucessfully be treated according to arm 1. Since the positive effect of high dose induction was lost in the tiw dosing phase of treatment due to a 12% break through rate, viral elimination rates might be further increased by continuous daily application of CIFN and weight adjusted ribavirin dosing. Such a protocol is currently being evaluated in a larger multicenter trial.
UR  -  https://www.cochranelibrary.com/central/doi/10.1002/central/CN-00506268/full
