TI  -  A pilot randomized, controlled trial of the effect of iron depletion on long-term response to (alpha)-interferon in patients with chronic hepatitis C virus
JA  -  Hepatology (Baltimore, Md.)
PY  -  1996
VL  -  24
IS  -  4 (Pt 2)
CC  -  HS-HANDSRCH
CC  -  Hepato-Biliary
SP  -  405A
M3  -  Journal article
AB  -  Background: We previously showed phlebotomy induced iron (Fe) deficiency resulted in significant improvement in serum ALT levels, but no change in serum HCV RNA levels in patients with chronic HCV infection. Our preliminary results also suggested that phlebotomy may improve the response rate to [alpha]‐IFN. The aim of this study was to determine if phlebotomy induced Fe deficiency prior to [alpha]‐IFN improved the long‐term response rate. Methods: 38 patients with chronic HCV were randomized to either (1) undergo bi‐weekly phlebotomies until iron‐deficiency as defined by 2 of 3 criteria: serum iron < 50 µg/dl, transferrin saturation < 15%, > 3 gm/dl HgB drop from baseline or (2) observation for 6‐8 weeks. All patients then received [alpha]‐IFN (3 mu tiw for 6 months) and were followed for an additional 6 months after discontinuation of [alpha]‐IFN. Patients were defined as complete responders (CR; no detectable serum HCV RNA after 6 months of [alpha]‐IFN), sustained responders (SR; no detectable serum HCV RNA 6 months after stopping [alpha]‐IFN), or non‐responders (NR; detectable serum HCV RNA after 3 months of [alpha]‐IFN therapy). Results: There was no significant difference in age, gender, disease duration, genotype, or histology between the groups. Outcomes were as follows: (Table). Conclusion: This study suggests that phlebotomy induced Fe deficiency may improve the long‐term response to [alpha]‐IFN therapy. However, a statistical difference could not be demonstrated.
