AB  -  Background/Objectives: Bimekizumab (BKZ), a monoclonal antibody that selectively inhibits interleukin (IL) 17F in addition to IL‐17A, has shown sustained efficacy and safety to week 104 in patients across the full spectrum of axial spondyloarthritis (axSpA) in the phase 3 studies BE MOBILE 1 (nonradiographic [nr‐]axSpA) and 2 (radiographic [r‐]axSpA), and their openlabel extension.1 Achievement of remission is a treatment goal and may guide clinical decisions (2).We report achievement of remission defined using objective signs of inflammation (OSIs) in patients with axSpAversus an established measure of remission, the Axial Spondyloarthritis Disease Activity Score <1.3 (ASDAS‐Inactive Disease [ID]). Methods: BEMOBILE 1 (NCT03928704) and 2 (NCT03928743) comprised a 16‐week double‐blind, placebo (PBO)‐controlled period followed by a 36‐week maintenance period. Patients were randomized to subcutaneous BKZ 160 mg every 4 weeks or PBO; all patients received BKZ from week 16 onward. OSI remission comprised magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) remission of the sacroiliac joints and spine (MRI Spondyloarthritis Research Consortium of Canada sacroiliac joint score <2 and Berlin MRI spine ≤2), C‐reactive protein ≤5mg/L, and a swollen joint count of 0.Data are reported using observed cases. Results: This analysis included 152 and 139 patients from the BE MOBILE 1 and 2MRI substudies, respectively. Baseline OSI levels were similar across treatment arms in patients with nr‐axSpAand r‐axSpA. In patients with nr‐axSpA, 32/ 74 (43.2%) BKZ‐randomized and 11/59 (18.6%) PBO‐randomized patients achieved week 16 OSI remission, versus 16/74 (21.6%) and 5/59 (8.5%) achieving ASDAS ID, respectively. Thirty‐two of 63 (50.8%) BKZ‐randomized patients and 19/54 (35.2%) PBO‐to‐BKZ switchers achieved week 52 OSI remission, versus 22/63 (34.9%) and 21/54 (38.9%) achieving ASDAS ID, respectively (Figure 1). In patients with r‐axSpA, 32/79 (40.5%) BKZ‐randomized and 8/44 (18.2%) PBO‐randomized patients achieved week 16 OSI remission, versus 12/79 (15.2%) and 1/44 (2.3%) achieving ASDAS ID, respectively. Thirtyeight of 76 (50.0%) BKZ‐randomized patients and 20/39 (51.3%) PBO‐to‐ BKZ switchers achieved week 52 OSI remission, versus 18/76 (23.7%) and 18/39 (46.2%) achieving ASDAS ID, respectively (Figure 2). Conclusion: In general, a higher proportion of BKZ‐treated patients achieved remission defined by absence of OSI than ASDAS ID. This suggests that ASDAS ID could underestimate the anti‐inflammatory effects of BKZ, and there is a potential need for optimized endpoints to guide clinical management of axSpA. Funding: UCB.
