ients achieved week 16 OSI remission, versus 12/79 (15.2%) and 1/44 (2.3%) achieving ASDAS ID, respectively. Thirtyeight of 76 (50.0%) BKZ‐randomized patients and 20/39 (51.3%) PBO‐to‐ BKZ switchers achieved week 52 OSI remission, versus 18/76 (23.7%) and 18/39 (46.2%) achieving ASDAS ID, respectively (Figure 2). Conclusion: In general, a higher proportion of BKZ‐treated patients achieved remission defined by absence of OSI than ASDAS ID. This suggests that ASDAS ID could underestimate the anti‐inflammatory effects of BKZ, and there is a potential need for optimized endpoints to guide clinical management of axSpA. Funding: UCB.
