DO  -  10.1016/S1590-8658(10)60491-4
AB  -  Background and Aims: HCV genotype and HCV‐RNA decline at week 4 and 12 can be used to shorten (by 12 and 24 weeks) or prolong (by 24 weeks) PegIFN+RBV standard therapy. Modelling the decline of the infected cells, instead, can exactly calculate treatment duration in the individual patient. We tested in a randomised controlled trial duration and efficacy of model tailored (MT) vs Guide Line (GL) approaches. Patients and Methods: One hundred consecutive patients (38 naïve ‐ 62 retreated, 60 Gen.1‐4 and 40 Gen.2‐3, 60 peg‐IFN 2a and 40 2b), were stratified and randomised 1:1 to GL or MT schedules. GL duration was 24 weeks for Gen.2‐3 and 48 weeks for Gen.1‐4. Week 12 stopping rule was applied in Gen.1 non responders (NR). ALT and HCV‐RNA were measured in MT patients at day 0‐2‐4‐7‐ 14‐21‐28 to compute the Ieot index (infected cell number at the end of therapy) and, if Ieot(GL)>5000, treatment was stopped at week 4, otherwise tailored to achieve Ieot<250. Results: Ieot could be computed in 42 (84%) MT patients, the remaining 8 were switched to GL (not included in the analysis). Therapy was withdrawn/modified because of side effects in 13 (26%) MT and in 9 (18%) GL patients; 11 (22%) MT and 8 (16%) GL patients were NR. Per protocol analysis showed SVR rates of 85% in MT and 82% in GL schedules. Individual treatment duration to achieve SVR in MT patients was a continuous variable related only in part to the genotype: 18‐55 weeks in 7 Gen.1, 13‐21 weeks in 3 Gen.2 and 21‐56 weeks in 5 Gen.3 patients. Treatment duration for SVR was 21% longer in GL than MT patients. Treatment failure was less frequently due to a relapse in MT as compared to GL patients (21% vs 43%). Conclusions: PegIFN+RBV duration can be individually modulated with accuracy in most HCV patients by modelling the infected cell decline. This approach improves the cost/efficacy of the antiviral therapy and could better guide the re‐treatment of patients with previous relapse.
