AB  -  Aims: To report achievement of remission defined by objective signs of inflammation (OSI) in patients with axial spondyloarthritis (axSpA), versus an established measure, Axial Spondyloarthritis Disease Activity Score < 1.3 (ASDAS Inactive Disease [ID]), using data from randomized controlled trials BE MOBILE 1&amp;2. 41 of 70 Methods: BE MOBILE 1 (NCT03928704)&amp;2 (NCT03928743) comprised 16‐week (wk) double‐blind, placebo (PBO) controlled+ 36‐wk maintenance periods. Patients were randomized to bimekizumab (BKZ) 160 mg every 4 wks (Q4W) or PBO; all received BKZ from Wk16. OSI remission comprised MRI remission of sacroiliac joints (SIJ) and spine (MRI Spondyloarthritis Research Consortium of Canada [SPARCC] SIJ score < 2, Berlin MRI spine ≤ 2), C‐reactive protein (CRP) ≤ 5 mg/L, and swollen joint count (SJC) = 0. Proportion of patients (observed case) achieving OSI remission versus ASDAS ID was compared. Results: 152 and 139 patients were included from BE MOBILE 1 and 2 MRI sub‐studies, respectively. Baseline OSI levels were similar across treatment arms in patients with nr‐axSpA and r‐axSpA; generally, baseline MRI SPARCC SIJ/Berlin MRI spine/ high sensitivity‐CRP/ SJC/ASDAS/BASDAI/BASFI scores and time since first axSpA symptoms were lower in patients achieving Wk16 OSI remission versus non‐responders. Among patients with nr‐axSpA, 43.2% (32/74) BKZ‐randomized and 18.6% (11/59) PBO‐randomized patients achieved Wk16 OSI remission, versus 21.6% (16/74) and 8.5%(5/59) achieving ASDAS ID, respectively. 50.8%(32/63) BKZ‐randomized patients and 35.2% (19/54) PBO‐to‐ BKZ switchers achieved Wk52 OSI remission, versus 34.9% (22/63) and 38.9% (21/54) achieving ASDAS ID, respectively. In patients with r‐axSpA, 40.5% (32/79) BKZ‐randomized and 18.2% (8/44) PBO‐randomized patients achieved Wk16 OSI remission, versus 15.2% (12/79) and 2.3% (1/44) achieving ASDAS ID, respectively. 50.0% (38/76) BKZ‐randomized patients and 51.3% (20/39) PBO‐to‐ BKZ switchers achieved Wk52 OSI remission, versus 23.7% (18/76) and 46.2% (18/39) achieving ASDAS ID, respectively. Conclusion: Generally, a higher proportion of BKZ‐treated patients achieved remission defined by absence of OSI than ASDAS ID. Findings suggest that ASDAS ID could underestimate the anti‐inflammatory effects of BKZ, while highlighting a potential need for optimized endpoints guiding clinical management of axSpA. Funding: UCB.
