DO  -  10.1111/imj.15756
AB  -  Aim: Evaluate responses to ixekizumab (IXE) treatment in patients with axial spondyloarthritis (axSpA), stratified by hsCRP and its change from baseline to Week 16. Method: COAST‐V, COAST‐W, and COAST‐X were phase 3, multicenter, randomised, controlled trials investigating the efficacy of IXE 80 mg every 4 (Q4W) and 2 weeks (Q2W) in patients with radiographic axSpA (r‐axSpA) and non‐radiographic axSpA (nr‐axSpA). This post hoc analysis focused on IXE 80 mg Q4W. Using a CRP cutoff of 5 mg/L, patients were stratified according to the responses to IXE 80 mg Q4W over 16 weeks into stable low, normalised and elevated groups. Result: Mean MRI SPARCC scores at baseline were higher in patients with normalised (21.8) and elevated hsCRP (20.7) compared to those with stable low hsCRP (6.7). Baseline disease activity measured using BASDAI, ASDAS and spinal pain were similar between groups. Achievement of ASAS40 and BASDAI50 responses was observed in all the three categories of hsCRP changes in IXE‐treated patients compared to placebo over 16 weeks. The highest ASAS 40 and BASDAI50 responses rate was reported in patients with normalised hsCRP. These findings were similar across the COAST‐V, COAST‐W and COAST‐X trials. Conclusions: Treatment with IXE reduced clinical disease activity in both bDMARD‐naïve and TNFi‐experienced patients across the axSpA spectrum and across categories of hsCRP changes from baseline to Week 16.
