AB  -  Introduction: Vitamin D deficiency is common in the Irish population, primarily due to reduced cutaneous synthesis of Vitamin D from sunlight at Irish latitudes for 4 to 6 months per year. Vitamin D deficiency is associated with adverse health outcomes including osteomalacia, decreased muscle strength and function and increased falls risk. In 2017, a screening program for Bone Health in persons with Hemophilia commenced at the National Coagulation Centre. This study evaluates for the first time the prevalence of low Vitamin D levels in persons with severe Hemophilia (PWSH) resident in Ireland. Methods: All patients in Ireland with Hemophilia are registered with the National Coagulation Centre. Adult patients (>16 years) with severe Factor VIII or Factor IX deficiency were identified from the National Haemophilia Electronic Record. Results of laboratory Bone Health screening (comprising blood sampling for corrected calcium, phosphate, magnesium, Vitamin D, Parathyroid hormone (PTH), testosterone and C‐reactive protein (CRP) levels) from September 2016 to September 2017 were reviewed. Results: In total, 108 PWSH were identified of whom 85 (79%) have undergone bone health screening within the 12 month study period. Vitamin D levels were normal in 46 patients (54%) and were low (≤50 nmol/L) in 39 patients (46%). Of the 39 patients with low Vitamin D levels, 28 had FVIII and 11 FIX deficiency, while 21 had previous infection with Hepatitis C and 2 had HIV infection. Vitamin D levels were <30 nmol/L in 19 individuals and between 30 and 50 nmol/L in 20 individuals. Calcium, phosphate and magnesium levels were normal in this patient group (medians 2.35 mmol/L, 1.13 mmol/L and 0.84 mmol/L respectively. Two patients had elevated PTH levels of 94.5 and 96 pg/mL (NR 15‐65 pg/mL). Four patients had testosterone levels less than the lower limit of normal. All patients with low Vitamin D levels have commenced oral Vitamin D supplements. Discussion/Conclusion: In common with the general Irish population, PWSH in Ireland have a relatively high prevalence of low Vitamin D levels. Low Vitamin D levels have been associated with poor muscle function, increased falls and contribute to poor bone health. Intervention to correct low Vitamin D levels with a once daily oral supplement is cost‐effective and well tolerated.
