AB  -  Purpose: To assess safety within the first 30 post‐op days of placement of 6x6 cm Strattice™ tissue matrix (TM) stoma reinforcement at the time of stoma construction. Methods: Patients were prospectively randomized to undergo standard end stoma construction with (S) or without (NR) Strattice™ TM reinforcement. All patients undergoing stoma construction with the expectation of having their stoma in place for a minimum of one year were eligible. 113 patients were enrolled: 58 in the NR and 55 in the S group. 59 men and 54 women of a mean age of 60 years, a mean BMI of 25.4 kg/m2 and a mean ASA of 2.1 were assessed. There were no significant differences between the NR and S groups relative to gender, ethnicity, ASA score, BMI, indication for surgery, preoperative stoma site marking, bowel preparation, oral antibiotic administration, rectus muscle condition or type of procedure. Ileostomy (S=19, NR=24) and colostomy (S=36, NR=34) construction was similar between the groups. Results: Intraoperative complications and blood loss were similar between the groups. Stoma complications at 30 days (necrosis [1], prolapse [1], and stenosis [1]) were not significantly different between the groups but were more frequent in the control group (17.2% vs 12.7%). No parastomal hernias or fistulas were noted in either group and no Strattice™ removal was necessary; stoma quality of life scores were similar (NR=58.98 v S=62.37). Conclusions: Safety and quality of life data from this randomized control trial show similar outcomes in both groups.
