DO  -  10.1016/S0168-8278(12)61417-2
AB  -  Background: Alisporivir (ALV) is a host targeting antiviral (HTA) with pangenotypic anti‐HCV activity and high barrier to viral resistance. The FUNDAMENTAL (A2210) study is a large international, double‐blind, placebo‐controlled study including HCV‐G1 non‐responder (NR) and relapser patients, treated with 3 different doses of ALV+PR vs PR alone. Primary endpoint was superiority of ALV+PR in the proportion of cEVR patients (week 12 undetectable HCVRNA) in this difficult to treat population. Materials and Methods: 461 patients were stratified by BMI, IL28B genotype and previous treatment response then randomized to 4 treatment arms (ALV600QD, n = 121; ALV800QD, n = 117, ALV400BID, n = 109) and PR, n = 114. All patients have completed 12 weeks treatment, and will receive a total of 48 weeks, followed to SVR24 (week 72). 51% NR (null‐NR: Partial‐NR = 6.4:3.1), 43% relapsers (total 5% missing data); HCV‐G1a:G1b = 3:7, 24% compensated cirrhosis. Well balanced treatment arms had 77% Caucasian, 18% Asian; 3% Black. 79% IL28BCT/TT genotype. Results: ALV‐based treatment had superior RVR vs PR (41% ALV400BID, p < 0.0001; 25% ALV800QD, 22% ALV600QD vs 7% PR. For primary endpoint, all ALV arms had superior cEVR vs PR (72% ALV400BID p < 0.00001; 61% ALV800QD; 46% ALV600QD, vs 33% PR). NR had the greatest cEVR benefit vs PR, (70% ALV400BID; 48% ALV800QD, 34% ALV600QD vs 14% PR). All ALV doses were effective in achieving response, and with ALV400BID 68% of Partial NR and 70%Null NR reached cEVR. Relapsers achieved cEVR 78% with ALV800 QD vs 52% PR, (p = 0.005). IL28BCT/TT patients achieved superior cEVR rates (69% ALV400BID) compared to 25% PR. IL28BCC patients achieved up to 90% cEVR with ALV treatment (vs 39% PR). Well‐tolerated treatment with very few and similar rates of discontinuations due to AEs/SAEs across all arms. ALV400BID, had more frequent GI AEs, thrombocytopenia or neutropenia vs PR, but these were not severe and had not led to more frequent treatment discontinuations. Conclusion: Alisporivir at all doses used in combination with PR achieved high rates of negative HCV‐RNA, however ALV400BID was the most efficacious. The difference was particularly pronounced in non‐responders and CT/TT patients, offering a promising new treatment option for difficult to treat HCV‐G1 patients.
