DO  -  10.1111/1756-185X.13984
AB  -  Background: PREVENT (NCT02696031) is the first Phase III, randomized placebo‐controlled study evaluating secukinumab 150 mg with (LD) and without (NL) loading, in patients with non‐radiographic axial spondyloarthritis (nr‐axSpA). There were 2 independent analysis plans to meet EU &amp; non‐US (Week 16) and US (Week 52) regulatory requirements. Here, we report pre‐defined exploratory analysis of the efficacy of secukinumab in tumor necrosis factor inhibitor (TNFi)‐naïve patients with nr‐axSpA through Week 52 from the PREVENT study. Methods: Patients fulfilling ASAS criteria for axSpA plus abnormal CRP and/or MRI, without evidence of radiographic changes in sacroiliac joints (modified New York Criteria for Ankylosing Spondyloarthritis) were randomized (1:1:1) to secukinumab 150 mg LD, NL, or placebo at baseline, Weeks 1, 2, and 3, and then every 4 weeks starting at Week 4. NL patients received placebo at Weeks 1, 2, and 3. Switch to open‐label secukinumab 150 mg or standard of care was permitted after Week 20. Primary endpoints were ASAS40 responses at Week 16 (LD) and at Week 52 (NL) in TNFi‐naïve patients. Exploratory endpoints in TNFi‐naïve patients through Week 52 included BASDAI50, ASAS partial remission, ASQoL, SI joint edema on MRI, ASDAS‐CRP and CRP inactive disease. Results: In total 90.3% (501/555) of TNFi‐naïve patients received secukinumab 150 mg LD (N = 164), NL (N = 166) and placebo (N = 171). The primary endpoints were met; ASAS40 responses in TNFi‐naïve patients were significantly higher with secukinumab (41.5% for LD at Week 16 and 39.8% for NL at Week 52) vs placebo (29.2% at Week 16 and 19.9% at Week 52; P < 0.05 for both). Secukinumab 150 mg also improved all other efficacy parameters vs placebo in TNFi‐naïve patients (Table). Conclusions: Secukinumab 150 mg provided significant and sustained improvement in signs and symptoms, disease activity, and quality of life in TNFi‐naïve patients with nr‐axSpA through Week 52.
