DO  -  10.1111/1756-185X.15172
AB  -  Aim: Bimekizumab (BKZ) is a monoclonal IgG1 antibody that selectively inhibits interleukin (IL)‐17F in addition to IL‐17A. Here, we report low disease activity (LDA) achievement, defined by Ankylosing Spondylitis (AS) Disease Activity Score (ASDAS) < 2.1, Bath AS Disease Activity Index (BASDAI) < 4, or both, to Week (Wk) 52 with BKZ. Method: BE MOBILE 1 (NCT03928704; non‐radiographic axial spondyloarthritis [nr‐axSpA]) and 2 (NCT03928743; r‐axSpA) each comprised a 16‐wk placebo (PBO)‐controlled and 36‐wk maintenance period. All patients had active disease (BASDAI ≥4 and spinal pain ≥4 as per BASDAI item 2) at baseline. Patients received BKZ 160 mg every 4 weeks (Q4W) or PBO; all received BKZ 160 mg Q4W from Wk16 onwards. Proportion of LDA achievers to Wk52 are presented using non‐responder imputation. Results: Overall, 254 patients with nr‐axSpA (BKZ: 128, PBO: 126) and 332 with r‐axSpA (BKZ: 221, PBO: 111) were randomised. Most had high (ASDAS ≥2.1‐≤3.5)/very high (ASDAS >3.5) baseline disease activity (nr‐axSpA: BKZ: 99.2%, PBO: 97.6%; r‐axSpA: BKZ: 98.6%, PBO: 100%). In patients with nr‐axSpA, a greater proportion of BKZ versus PBO‐treated patients achieved LDA at Wk16 according to ASDAS < 2.1/BASDAI < 4/both (BKZ: 46.1%/52.3%/43.8%, PBO: 19.8%/31.7%/19.0%). Separation from PBO was apparent from first post‐baseline assessment for ASDAS < 2.1, and both ASDAS < 2.1 and BASDAI < 4. Results were similar for patients with r‐axSpA. Across continuous BKZ‐treated patients and PBO/BKZ switchers, LDA achievement was sustained or improved in both studies to Wk52. Proportion of patients achieving BASDAI < 4 was consistently higher than ASDAS < 2.1 achievement, regardless of treatment arm. Conclusion: Across the axSpA disease spectrum, inhibition of IL‐17A and IL‐17F with BKZ resulted in rapid LDA achievement versus PBO to Wk16. Proportion of LDA achievers increased to Wk52. These data suggest that ASDAS < 2.1 is a more stringent LDA criteria than BASDAI < 4; most ASDAS < 2.1 achievers also achieved BASDAI < 4. This is relevant when considering BKZ within a potential treat‐to‐ target approach for patients with axSpA in daily practice.
