AB  -  Background/Objectives: Bimekizumab (BKZ) is a monoclonal IgG1 antibody that selectively inhibits interleukin 17F in addition to interleukin 17A. Treatment with BKZ was efficacious and well‐tolerated to week 104 across the full disease spectrum of axial spondyloarthritis (axSpA) in 2 phase 3 studies, BEMOBILE 1 (nonradiographic [nr‐]axSpA) and 2 (radiographic [r‐]axSpA), and their openlabel extension.1 Patients often ask their health care providers, How quickly will I feel better after starting this newdrug?Here, we assess the rapidity of treatment response in BKZ‐treated patients with axSpA, from 2 phase 3 studies. Methods: BE MOBILE 1 (NCT03928704) and 2 (NCT03928743) were double‐ blind, comprising 16‐week placebo (PBO)‐controlled and 36‐week maintenance periods. Patients were randomized to BKZ 160 mg every 4 weeks or PBO; all received BKZ from week 16 onward.We present treatment responses toweek 16 for the BKZ and PBO arms, including Kaplan‐Meier analyses of the Assessment of SpondyloArthritis international Society 40% (ASAS40) response, using observed case. Nonresponder imputation and multiple imputation were applied for missing binary and continuous outcomes, respectively. Aside from p values reported at week 16 for ranked primary (ASAS40) and secondary endpoints, all other p values are nominal. Results: Of 254 patients enrolled in BEMOBILE 1 (BKZ: 128; PBO: 126) and 332 in BE MOBILE 2 (BKZ: 221, PBO: 111), 96.1% (244/254) and 97.0% (322/332) completed to week 16, respectively. Kaplan‐Meier analyses showed early separation between BKZ and PBO for ASAS40 (Figure), with a greater proportion of ASAS40 responders after a single baseline BKZ dose, from week 1 for nr‐axSpA (16.4% vs. 1.6%; nominal p < 0.05) and week 2 for r‐axSpA (16.7% vs. 7.2%; nominal p < 0.05). ASAS40 response rates continued to increase toweek 16 in all patients. For many of the other endpoints, separation between BKZ versus PBO was observed after a single baseline BKZ dose, from week 1 onward in nr‐axSpA and week 2 onward in r‐axSpA. This included the proportion of patients achieving Axial Spondyloarthritis Disease Activity Score low disease activity (<2.1). Further outcomes including spinal pain and physical function also improved. Conclusion: BKZ‐treated patients across the full disease spectrum of axSpA achieved rapid treatment responses, with separation from PBO as early as 1 to 2 weeks after a single baseline BKZ dose. These results are important for counseling patients with axSpA. Funding: UCB.
UR  -  https://www.cochranelibrary.com/central/doi/10.1002/central/CN-02871998/full
