AB  -  Background/Objective: Anti‐TNF agents are currently recommended for the treatment of NSAID‐resistant ankylosing spondylitis (AS), but limited data are available on their efficacy in non‐radiographic axial spondyloarthritis (nr‐axSpA) in patients from Latin America (LA), Central Europe, and Asia. The objective of this analysis was to compare the efficacy of etanercept (ETN) versus placebo after 12 weeks of double‐blind treatment in patients with nr‐axSpA who had an insufficient response to NSAIDs. Methods: Enrolled patients from LA, Central Europe, and Asia satisfied ASAS criteria for ax‐ SpA, without fulfilling modified NY criteria for AS, had symptom duration of 3 months‐ 5 years, BASDAI score ≥4 despite current NSAID use, and had failed ≥2 NSAIDs. Patients were randomized to ETN 50 mg weekly or placebo wtih background NSAID. Randomization was stratified by sacroiliitis (positive/negative on MRI) and by geographic region. The primary endpoint was ASAS40 at week 12. MRI of the spine and sacroiliac joints was performed at baseline and week 12 and analyzed using the SPARCC scoring method. Results: At baseline, 111 patients had a mean age of 32 years (range, 18‐48 years); 67% were male; and mean disease duration was 2.4 years (range, 4 months‐5 years). A total of 85%, 41%, and 88% were MRI+, had elevated CRP, or were MRI+ and/or CRP+, respectively; 75% and 9% were HLA‐B27+ or had psoriasis. A greater proportion of patients in the ETN group (Table Presented) versus placebo group achieved ASAS40 and experienced greater improvements in all other clinical endpoints at week 12; ETN was associated with significant improvements versus placebo in SPARCC scores, back pain, inflammation on MRI, and PGA (P < 0.05). Conclusions: In this population of patients from LA, Central Europe, and Asia with early, active nr‐axSpA who had an inadequate response to ≥2 NSAIDs, ETN was more effective than placebo in decreasing disease activity and inflammation on MRI.
