AB  -  Background: A decade ago the silastic ring was used to provide greater dietary restriction to Roux‐en‐Y gastric bypass (RYGB) surgery. Its purpose was to prevent the effects of possible dilation of the gastrojejunal anastomosis and late weight gain. In 2010, a clinical trial randomized 400 patients to open RYGB in two groups: with (WR) and without ring (NR). Statistical analyses were performed 2 years after, n=361. Now these patients are being interviewed to analyze the effects of the silastic ring in RYGB after 10 years of randomized intervention evaluating: differences in body weight evolution, vomiting and quality of life between the two groups. Methods: Active search through direct contact at the multidisciplinary clinic, using a questionnaire about weight, vomit index and quality of life. Data were analyzed with BioEstat 5.3 version software. The p value was considered significant if <0.05. Medical Research Ethics Committee approval number 3.309/2009. Results: 171 questionnaires were applied out of 224 contacted, 82 WR and 89 NR, 13 patients died, 5 from surgery‐related causes and 1 denial. 140 unsuccessful attempted contact. The excess weight loss (EWL) in the WR was 59.58% (NR 54.57% p=0.37), the vomiting rate in WR sample was 89.02% (NR 42.69% p<0.0001). 56.09% WR group said they felt better or much better about themselves, their work, social interaction and sex life (quality of life) after intervention, and 55.05% of the NR, with no significant difference (p=0.4). The weight regain rate [(current weight‐reported minimum weight)x100/(pre‐op weightminimum weight)] in the WR was 36.12% and in the NR was 38.75% (p=0.34). Conclusions: After 10 years, the placement of silastic ring resulted in higher vomiting rate and didn't show better performance in weight regain rate, quality of life and excess weight loss. This result differs from the analysis performed 2 years after the intervention, which found a more relevant difference in EWL (p=0.002). Only 47.93% of the original sample was analyzed, so results can change if more patients are found.
