AB  -  Introduction: Diabetes mellitus (DM) prognostic role in stage IV NETs isn't defined. Aim(s): We evaluated impact of DM on PFS in pts with advanced, non‐functioning GEP‐NETs. Materials and methods: We performed post hoc analysis from the phase III double‐blind, placebo‐controlled CLARINET study (NCT00353496) to investigate association between DM (any of: medical history of type 1 or 2; use of hypoglycemic drugs; HbA1c ≥6.5%, fasting plasma glucose ≥7mmol/L; non‐fasting plasma glucose ≥11.11mmol/L [at baseline or during study]) and PFS (Kaplan‐Meier). Multivariate Cox analysis was used to test interaction DM‐LAN efficacy. Results: The overall population (total, n=204; LAN, n=101; PBO, n=103) had well‐differentiated (Ki‐67 <10%) foregut (45%), midgut (36%), or hindgut (7%) and unknown (13%) NETs. 79 pts had DM; 24 received metformin plus LAN (n=14) or PBO (n=10). Median PFS (mPFS) was 96.0 months (mo) [95% CI: 70.4; not reached (NR)] for DM vs 98.0 mo [72.1; NR] for N‐DM (HR 1.20 [0.79;1.82], p=0.38). For DM, mPFS with LAN (n=42) was NR [95.9; NR] vs 60.0 mo [48.0;74.4] with PBO (n=37) (HR 0.27, [0.13‐0.57], p=0.0002). For N‐DM, mPFS with LAN (n=59) was NR [96.0; NR] vs 72.1 mo [52.0; NA] with PBO (n=66) (HR 0.64 [0.35‐1.15], p=0.04). In multivariate analysis, PFS wasn't associated with baseline DM (HR 1.64 [0.95;2.84], p=0.08). LAN confirmed its impact on PFS (HR 0.53 [0.31;0.89], p=0.02), without significant interaction between LAN efficacy and DM (p=0.62). Conclusion: DM wasn't a negative prognostic factor in stage IV GEP‐NETs. Efficacy of LAN in DM and N‐DM was confirmed, LAN‐DM interaction was not significant, LAN efficacy seemed favorable in DM compared to N‐DM patients. These findings should be evaluated in prospective biomarker studies.
UR  -  https://www.cochranelibrary.com/central/doi/10.1002/central/CN-02010776/full
