DO  -  10.1093/rheumatology/keu115.009
AB  -  Background: Adalimumab (ADA) is currently approved in the EU for the treatment of severe non‐radiographic axial spondyloarthritis (nraxSpA), in patients (pts) with an elevated CRP and/or positive MRI who have had an inadequate response to, or are intolerant to NSAIDs. Short‐term and 1 year remission data have been previously reported for the ABILITY‐1 trial. The study assessed drug survival and durability of clinical remission at year 2 among pts with nr‐axSpA. Methods: ABILITY‐1 is an ongoing phase 3, double blind (DB), randomized, controlled trial in pts with nr‐axSpA who had an inadequate response, intolerance, or contraindication to NSAIDs. A 12‐week DB period of ADA 40mg every other week (eow) or placebo (PBO) was followed by an open‐label (OL) extension phase in which pts could receive OL ADA 40mg eow for up to an additional 144 weeks. This post hoc analysis evaluated the week 104 efficacy and safety of ADA in the MRI+/elevated CRP nr‐axSpA subpopulation, defined as pts who had a positive baseline (BL) MRI (SPARCC score ≥2 for either the SI joints or spine) or an elevated CRP at BL. Clinical remission was defined by ASDAS inactive disease (ASDAS ID, ASDAS <1.3) or by ASAS partial remission (ASAS PR). Sustained remission was defined as achieving clinical remission at weeks 52, 80, and 104. Clinical responses were summarized by observed case analysis. Safety was assessed in terms of adverse events (AE). Results: 142 (69 ADA, 73 PBO) of the total efficacy population (N=185) were in the MRI+/elevated CRP subpopulation; 107 (75%) had data available for week 104 analysis. Table 1 lists clinical response and sustained remission rates for the MRI+/elevated CRP subpopulation. Sustained remission rates were similar between pts with symptom duration <5 vs ≥5 years (sustained ASDAS ID 38% vs 31%; sustained ASAS PR 26% vs 29%). Among pts exposed to ADA during the study (356.2 patient‐years [PY] of exposure) there were 8 serious infections (2.2/100 PY, including 1 case of disseminated TB), 1 case of lupus‐like syndrome, and 2 deaths (suicide and cardiopulmonary failure due to opiate toxicity). No malignancies or demyelinating diseases have been reported. Conclusion: Almost half of the pts who remained on long‐term ADA therapy in ABILITY‐1 were in remission at week 104, the majority of whom were also in this state of remission at weeks 52 and 80. Longterm safety data are comparable to the known AE rates with ADA in other rheumatology indications. (Table Presented).
