AB  -  Objectives: Non‐radiographic axial spondyloarthritis (nr‐axSpA) belongs to the spectrumof axSpA. PREVENT, a phase III placebo (PBO)‐controlled study Topics, evaluated efficacy and safety of secukinumab (SEC) 150mg with (LD) or without loading (NL) in nr‐axSpA patients. This study had 2 independent analysis plans as per EU(Week [Wk] 16) andUS (Wk52) regulatory requirements. Here, we report Wk16 efficacy and safety results up to Wk20. Methods: Patients (N=555; aged ≥18 years) fulfilling ASAS classification criteria for axSpA plus abnormal CRP and/or MRI, with no radiographic changes in the sacroiliac joints meeting modified New York Criteria, were randomized (1:1:1) to subcutaneous SEC 150mg LD, NL, or PBO. The LD and PBO groups received SEC 150mg or PBO, respectively, at baseline, Wks 1, 2, 3, and 4, and then every 4 wks. NL group received SEC 150mg at baseline and PBOatWks 1, 2, and 3, and then SEC150mg q4wk starting atWk4.Primary endpoint was ASAS40 response with 150mg SEC LD in anti‐TNF‐naïve patients at Wk16. Secondary endpoints included ASAS40, BASDAI, BASDAI50, BASFI, SF‐36 PCS, ASQoL, and ASAS partial remission. Endpoints were analyzed according to a predefined statistical hierarchy. Safety analyses included all patients who received ≥1 dose of treatment. Results: 94.6% (175/185; SEC LD), 96.2% (177/184; SEC NL) and 94.1% (175/186; PBO) of patients completed 24 wks. The primary and all secondary endpoints were met. ASAS40 in anti‐TNF‐naïve patients was significantly higher in SEC LD than PBO at Wk16 (Table). No new/unexpected safety signals were reported. Conclusions: SEC 150mg LD and NL provided significant improvement in signs and symptoms of nr‐axSpA. The safety profile of SECwas consistentwith the established safety profile across indications.1.
