DO  -  10.1111/1756-185X.15346
AB  -  Background/Purpose: Bimekizumab (BKZ), a monoclonal IgG1 antibody that selectively inhibits IL‐17F in addition to IL‐17A, demonstrated sustained efficacy and safety to Week (Wk)52 in patients with non‐radiographic (nr‐) and radiographic axial spondyloarthritis (r‐axSpA) in phase 3 studies BE MOBILE 1 and 2, respectively. 1 BKZ 52‐wk efficacy and safety in patients with r‐axSpA from China was consistent with the overall population.2 Here, we present 52‐wk results for BKZ in patients with nr‐axSpA from China. Methods: BE MOBILE 1 comprised a 16‐wk double‐blind, placebo (PBO)‐controlled period and 36‐wk maintenance period. From Wk16, patients received BKZ 160 mg every four wks (Q4W). Eligible patients were aged ≥18 years with active nr‐axSpA fulfilling ASAS classification criteria, without radiographic sacroiliitis. In this pre‐specified analysis of patients from China, we report Wk52 efficacy endpoints (imputation methods: Table/Figure) and treatment‐emergent adverse events (TEAEs; MedDRA v19.0) to Wk52 and beyond. Results: Of the patients randomised (BKZ = 18, PBO = 18), 35/36 (97.2%) completed Wk16 and 32/36 (88.9%) Wk52. Baseline characteristics were generally comparable across treatment subgroups (Table). All efficacy outcomes, including ASAS40 and ASAS PR, had greater Wk16 improvements from baseline with BKZ vs PBO (ASAS40: BKZ = 38.9%, PBO = 22.2%; ASAS PR: BKZ = 33.3%, PBO = 11.1%) with further improvement to Wk52 in both BKZ‐and PBO/BKZ‐randomised patients (ASAS40: BKZ = 44.4%, PBO/BKZ = 50.0%; ASAS PR: BKZ = 44.4%, PBO/BKZ = 66.7%; Table). At Wk52, 87.8% BKZ and 83.3% PBO/BKZ‐randomised patients achieved ASDAS‐LDA (<2.1), and 53.1% and 56.6% achieved ASDAS‐ID (<1.3; Figure). At Wk52, most patients achieved complete resolution of enthesitis (Table). Reductions from baseline to Wk16 in objective signs of inflammation (SPARCC MRI SIJ score, Berlin MRI Spine score, hs‐CRP) and improvements in function (BASFI), spinal mobility (BASMI) and quality of life (ASQoL) were sustained and generally improved through Wk52. Overall, 33/36 (91.7%) patients had ≥1 TEAE on BKZ; most frequent (by preferred term) was upper respiratory tract infection (27.8%). Four (11.1%) patients had a serious TEAE; all resolved. Four (11.1%) patients had mild/moderate Tinea infection (pedis/versicolor); no other fungal infections reported. 13 (36.1%) patients had hepatic TEAEs; most (12/13) were liver enzyme elevations. The vast majority of hepatic events were transient and none led to discontinuation. No cases of suicidal ideation or behaviour, adjudicated definite/probable IBD, uveitis, major adverse cardiac events, active tuberculosis, serious fungal/opportunistic infections, malignancies, or deaths were reported. Conclusion: In patients with nr‐axSpA from China, BKZ demonstrated sustained efficacy improvements and a comparable safety profile to Wk52, consistent with the overall population;1 no new safety signals were observed. (Table present) (Figure present).
