DO  -  10.1016/j.atherosclerosis.2019.06.444
AB  -  Background and Aims: Data regarding the effect of dietary proteins on cardiovascular and cardiometabolic risk are limited. Therefore, we aimed to assess the effect of an acute high‐protein (HP) vs. medium‐protein (MP) diet on serum lipids, arterial stiffness, and 24‐h blood pressure, after a 34‐month protein intervention (the PREVIEW study, ClinicalTrials.gov Identifier: NCT01777893). Methods: Twenty‐two female and 16 male subjects (mean age 64.5±5.9 years; BMI 28.9±3.9 kg/m2) completed the 48‐hour respiratory chamber study, being fed in energy balance with either a HP: 25P/45CHO/30F or MP: 15P/55CHO/30F En% diet. The study was part of the PREVIEW study, a multicenter EU project (EU‐FP7‐nr. 312057) that aims to identify the most effective lifestyle components regarding diet and physical activity in the prevention of T2D, in participants with pre‐diabetes. Results: For study participants, long‐term changes in protein intake (HP vs. MP) during the intervention had no impact on baseline cardiometabolic risk markers of the acute protein intervention study. Increases in serum triglycerides during the respiration chamber experiment were less pronounced in the HP compared to the MP condition (treatment effect: 0.22 mmol/l [0.01; 0.42], P<0.001). Neither serum lipoproteins nor HOMA‐IR were different between conditions. Twenty‐four‐hour heart rate was higher with HP compared to MP (66.8±5.0 vs. 61.7±8.6 bpm, respectively, P<0.05), but 24‐hour blood pressure was unaffected. Protein intake had no effect on pulse wave analysis or pulse wave velocity. Conclusions: Acutely, HP was associated with a lower increase in serum triglyceride concentrations, potentially yielding cardiometabolic benefits.
