AB  -  Background: Spinal pain, morning stiffness and fatigue are major contributors to disease burden in patients with axial spondyloarthritis (axSpA), and these symptoms can impact daily physical function and health‐related quality of life (HRQoL). Bimekizumab (BKZ) is a monoclonal IgG1 antibody that selectively inhibits interleukin (IL)‐17F in addition to IL‐17A. BKZ has shown sustained improvements in spinal pain, morning stiffness, fatigue, physical function and overall HRQoL to Week 104 in patients with axSpA in the phase 3 studies BE MOBILE 1 and 2, and their combined open‐label extension (OLE).[1,2] Objectives: To report data on the impact of BKZ on spinal pain, morning stiffness, fatigue, physical function and HRQoL up to 3 years. Methods: BE MOBILE 1 (non‐radiographic [nr]‐axSpA; NCT03928704) and BE MOBILE 2 (radiographic [r‐]axSpA; NCT03928743) both comprised a 16‐week, double‐blind, placebo‐controlled period followed by a 36‐week maintenance period; from Week 16, all patients received subcutaneous BKZ 160 mg every 4 weeks (Q4W). At Week 52, eligible BE MOBILE 1 and 2 study participants could enter the 2‐year OLE (BE MOVING; NCT04436640). We report mean changes from baseline (CfB) of BE MOBILE 1 and 2 to Week 164 in total and nocturnal spinal pain, morning stiffness (mean of Bath Ankylosing Spondylitis Disease Activity Index [BASDAI] questions [Q]5 and 6), fatigue (BASDAI Q1), Bath Ankylosing Spondylitis Functional Index (BASFI), Ankylosing Spondylitis Quality of Life (ASQoL) and 36‐Item Short Form Survey Physical Component Summary (SF‐36 PCS) scores using multiple imputation (MI). We also report the proportion of patients achieving thresholds for low total spinal pain, nocturnal spinal pain, morning stiffness and BASFI (<2 or <4), meaningful improvement in fatigue (≥8‐point increase from baseline in Functional Assessment of Chronic Illness Therapy [FACIT]‐Fatigue) [3] and clinically meaningful ASQoL improvement (≥4‐point reduction from baseline) using non‐responder imputation (NRI) and modified (m)NRI. mNRI considered all visits following discontinuation due to adverse events or lack of efficacy as non‐response; all other missing data were imputed with MI and the response derived from the imputed values. Data were pooled for all randomised patients with nr‐axSpA and r‐axSpA randomised in BE MOBILE 1 and 2 (N=586). Results: Of 586 randomised patients with axSpA (nr‐axSpA: 254; r‐axSpA: 332), 494 (84.3%) patients (nr‐axSpA: 208; r‐axSpA: 286) entered the OLE at Week 52. Of these, 425/494 (86.0%) patients (nr‐axSpA: 175; r‐axSpA: 250) completed to Week 164. Improvements observed from baseline to Week 52 in total and nocturnal spinal pain and morning stiffness were sustained through Week 164 (CfB to Week 164: −4.3 for all; Figure 1). At Week 164, >50% of patients achieved scores <4 in total spinal pain, nocturnal spinal pain and morning stiffness (NRI/mNRI: 50.2/59.9%, 55.5/66.5% and 51.7/63.1%, respectively); and approximately a third of patients achieved scores <2 (28.7/32.5%, 36.3/41.5% and 29.2/34.2%, respectively). Fatigue improvements, as measured by BASDAI Q1 (CfB to Week 164: –3.5; Figure 1), were also sustained. Around half (NRI/mNRI: 45.2/55.5%) of patients achieved a meaningful improvement in FACIT‐Fatigue (≥8‐point increase in those with a score of ≤44 at baseline [n=520]) at Week 164. Similar sustained improvements from Week 52 to Week 164 were observed for measures of physical function (BASFI CfB to Week 164: −2.9) and HRQoL (SF‐36 PCS CfB to Week 164: +12.3; ASQoL CfB to Week 164: −5.6; Figure 2). At Week 164, >50% of patients achieved a BASFI score of <4 (NRI/mNRI: 50.7/63.4%) and around a third achieved a score of <2 (28.3/34.2%). >50% of patients (NRI/mNRI: 55.6/66.7%) achieved a clinically meaningful ASQoL improvement (≥4‐point reduction in those with a score of ≥4 at baseline [n=504]). Conclusion: 3 years of BKZ treatment led to consistently sustained improvements in key symptoms including spinal pain, morning stiffness and fatigue, as well as in physical function and HRQoL in patients across the full disease spectrum of axSpA. These findings emphasise the long‐term value of BKZ in addressing symptoms which are central to the patient experience and profoundly affect their daily lives. REFERENCES: [1] Marzo‐Ortega H. Arthritis Rheumatol 2024;76:0592. [2] Navarro‐Compán V. Arthritis Rheumatol 2024;76:1480. [3] Cella D. J Patient Rep Outcomes 2024;8:92. [Figure presented][Figure presented] Acknowledgements: Funded by UCB. Medical writing support provided by Costello Medical and funded by UCB. Disclosure of Interests: Victoria Navarro‐Compán Speakers bureau for AbbVie, Eli Lilly, Fresenius Kabi, Janssen, MSD, Novartis, Pfizer and UCB, Consultant for AbbVie, Eli Lilly, Galapagos, Moonlake, MSD, Novartis, Pfizer and UCB, Grant/research support from AbbVie and Novartis, Uta Kiltz Consultancy fees from AbbVie, Amgen, Biocad, Biogen, BMS, Chugai, Eli Lilly, Fresenius, Gilead, Grünenthal, GSK, Hexal, Janssen, MSD, Novartis, onkowissen.de, Pfizer, Roche, UCB and Viatris, Grant and research support from AbbVie, Amgen, Biocad, Biogen, BMS, Chugai, Eli Lilly, Fresenius, Gilead, Grünenthal, GSK, Hexal, Janssen, MSD, Novartis, onkowissen.de, Pfizer, Roche, UCB and Viatris, Philip J. Mease Speakers bureau fees from AbbVie, Amgen, Eli Lilly and Company, Janssen, Novartis, Pfizer and UCB, Consulting fees from AbbVie, Acelyrin, Amgen, BMS, Cullinan, Eli Lilly and Company, GSK, Inmagene, Janssen, Moonlake Pharma, Novartis, Pfizer, Takeda, UCB and Ventyx, Grant/research support from AbbVie, Acelyrin, Amgen, BMS, Eli Lilly and Company, Janssen, Novartis, Pfizer, Sana and UCB, Maureen Dubreuil Consulting fees (e.g., advisory boards) from Amgen and UCB, Educational grant from Pfizer paid to institution, Karl Gaffney Speakers bureau for AbbVie, Eli Lilly, Novartis and UCB, Consultant of AbbVie, Eli Lilly, Novartis and UCB, Grant/research support from AbbVie, Gilead, Eli Lilly, Novartis and UCB, Atul Deodhar Speaker for Eli Lilly, J&amp;J, Novartis, Pfizer and UCB, Consultant for BMS, Eli Lilly, J&amp;J, MoonLake, Novartis, Pfizer and UCB, Grant/research support from BMS, Eli Lilly, J&amp;J, Novartis, Pfizer and UCB, Christine de la Loge Consultant for UCB, Diana Voiniciuc Employee of Veramed, Consultant for UCB, Jason Coarse Shareholder of UCB, Employee of UCB, Helena Marzo‐Ortega Speaking honoraria from AbbVie, Amgen, Biogen, Eli Lilly, Janssen, MoonLake, Novartis, Pfizer, Takeda and UCB, Consultancy fees from AbbVie, Amgen, Biogen, Eli Lilly, Janssen, MoonLake, Novartis, Pfizer, Takeda and UCB, Research grants from Janssen, Novartis, Pfizer and UCB. © The Authors 2025. This abstract is an open access article published in Annals of Rheumatic Diseases under the CC BY‐NC‐ND license (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by‐nc‐nd/4.0/). Neither EULAR nor the publisher make any representation as to the accuracy of the content. The authors are solely responsible for the content in their abstract including accuracy of the facts, statements, results, conclusion, citing resources etc.
