AB  -  Background &amp; Aims Studies implicated hepatic iron deposition in HCV infected patients the progression and the non‐response to therapy. The mechanism remains elusive. Previously, we reported increased expression of DMT1 in duodenal biopsies from patients with chronic hepatisti C. In this study, we assayed antibodies to DMT1 in the sera from hepatitis C‐infected patients who also received treatment. Methods: sera from patients with chronic hepatistis C who were treated with interferon‐ based therapy. Based on the response to therapy, patients were grouped : 23 patients responded (R ), and 71 patients were non‐responders (NR). The antibodies used in this study were rabbit polyclonal sera raised against putative extracellular loops of DMT1. The sequence of the synthetic peptides used for immunization and their location within the primary amino acid sequences were KPSQSQVLKGMTVP (anti‐DMT1 [174‐ 187] and VFAEAFFGKTNEQVVE (anti DMT1 [260‐275]. The detection of reactivity of antibodies to sera antigens was used by immuno dot blotting method. Results: A total 93 patients with mean age of 46.5 years (range 28‐65). There were 2 groups in this study: response (R) group and non‐response (NR) group. There were significant difference with respect to race, BMI (P<0.0001), baseline viral load (P<0.005) and the reactivity of anti‐DMT1 dot blotting (P < 0.0001) between 2 groups (Figure 1.). Conclusions: This is a preliminary study which documents for the first time significant reactivity to DMT1 in the sera of treated patients with hepatitis C, who failed treatment. While a larger randomized controlled trial would shed more light on this phenomenon, this observation suggests DMT1 antibodies titre may predict non‐response and may serve to monitor patients on treatment.
