AB  -  Background/Objectives: The Group for Research and Assessment of Psoriasis and Psoriatic Arthritis (GRAPPA) domain‐based treatment recommendations for psoriatic arthritis (PsA) focus on 6 key domains: peripheral arthritis, axial disease, enthesitis, dactylitis, skin psoriasis, nail psoriasis, and PsA‐related conditions uveitis and inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) (1). Bimekizumab (BKZ; inhibitor of interleukin [IL]‐17F in addition to IL‐17A) has demonstrated clinical efficacy up to 1 year in PsA, psoriasis, and axial spondyloarthritis (axSpA). Here, BKZ long‐term efficacy is shown across GRAPPA core domains up to 2 years in phase 3 PsA and axSpA trials. Methods: Patients received BKZ 160 mg or placebo (PBO) every 4 weeks (every 4 weeks) in BE OPTIMAL (NCT03895203; biologic DMARD [bDMARD]‐ naive PsA), BE COMPLETE (NCT03896581; tumor necrosis factor inhibitor‐ inadequate response [TNFi‐IR] PsA), and BE MOBILE 1 (NCT03928704; nonradiographic [nr‐]axSpA) and 2 (NCT03928743; r‐axSpA). All PBO‐randomized patients received BKZ 160 mg every 4 weeks from week 16. BE OPTIMALWk52 and BE COMPLETE Wk16 completers could enter BE VITAL (open‐label extension [OLE]; NCT04009499); BE MOBILE 1 and 2 Wk52 completers could enter BE MOVING (OLE; NCT04436640). Outcomes are reported by GRAPPA domain to Wk104 (BE OPTIMAL) and Wk100 (BE COMPLETE) in PsA; uveitis and IBD reported toWk104 (BE OPTIMAL; BE COMPLETE). Axial domain outcomes are reported to Wk104 (BE MOBILE 1 and 2) in axSpA, according to GRAPPA recommendations (1). Missing data: nonresponder and multiple imputation, or observed case. Results: Wk104/100 completion was similar across all trials (BE OPTIMAL: 598/712 [84.0%], BE COMPLETE: 322/400 [80.5%], BE MOBILE 1: 189/ 254 [74.4%], BE MOBILE 2: 267/332 [80.4%]). Baseline demographics and disease characteristics were previously reported. For all GRAPPA domains, 1‐year improvements were sustained to 2 years across all studies. Individual domain responses were generally consistent between bDMARD‐naive and TNFi‐IR patients (Figure 1). Axial domain improvements were sustained to 2 years in BE MOBILE 1 and 2 (Figure 2) and support BKZ efficacy for PsA axial disease (1). To Wk104, there were no instances of uveitis (BE OPTIMAL; BE COMPLETE). Four patients (0.6%) in BE OPTIMAL and none in BE COMPLETE had definite or probable adjudicated IBD. Conclusion: BKZ treatment resulted in robust improvement maintained to 2 years across GRAPPA domains with low rates of IBD and no uveitis in bDMARD‐naive and TNFi‐IR PsA; results in axSpA support efficacy in the axial domain.
