AB  -  Background: Antiretroviral therapy (ART) does not entirely restore immune function. 3S is a highly conserved gp41 motif that increases the expression of NKp44L on CD4 cells which subsequently became a target for NK‐induced cell death. A high level of anti‐3S Ab has been associated with lower HIV progression in untreated HIVinfected patients. We hypothesized that a vaccine against the 3S peptide motif (VAC‐3S) would decrease impact of HIV on CD4 cells Methods: IPROTECT, a randomized, placebo‐controlled clinical Phase 2 study (NCT02041247; Minka Tx, France), enrolled 86 HIV‐1 patients virologically controlled on ART with CD4 count < 500 cells/mm3 to receive VAC‐3S at 16μg (n=24), 32μg (n=25) at Week (W)0, 4, 8, 12, 36, 48, or 64μg (n=23) at W0, 4, 8, or placebo (n=10). Primary endpoint was immunogenicity defined as anti‐3S Ab >50AU after 3 vaccinations. Patients were categorized as non‐responders (NR), low (LR) or high responders (HR), according to the fold‐change in VAC‐3S Abs from baseline (ranged between < 4 to ≥10 fold). Markers for inflammation (CRP, IL6), activation (HLA‐DR, CD38), exhaustion (PD1), NKp44L and soluble sCD26 activities were assessed at baseline and W48 Results: VAC‐3S vaccine was safe. The proportion of VAC‐3S Ab responders was 63% (31/49) at the 16 or 32μg doses, 27% (5/23) at the 64μg dose, and no response in placebo arm (P< 0.0001). HR experienced, between baseline and W48 an increase in CD4 count (p=0.0029) a decrease in % PD1+CD4 cells (p=0.0021), in absence of inflammation and activation. Furthermore, anti‐3S Ab production was correlated positively with sDPP4 activity (p=0.0088, r=0.33), and negatively with functional NKp44L activity in CD4 cells (p< 0.0001; r=‐0.76) Conclusions: VAC‐3S appears to be safe and immunogenic. High anti‐3S Ab response was associated with an increase in CD4 count and a decrease in markers associated with CD4 cell exhaustion. Further development should consider personalized HIV vaccination in patients with high PD1 expression.
