DO  -  10.1002/hem3.70153
AB  -  Background The first‐line therapy in newly diagnosed immune thrombocytopenia (ITP) with corticosteroids, whether standard dose prednisolone or high dose dexamethasone has always been a matter of debate. Aims To compare the safety and efficacy of Standard Dose Prednisolone (PDN) and Pulsed High Dose Dexamethasone (HDDXM) therapy in newly diagnosed ITP patients (pts) at 4 weeks (wks)‐initial response and at 12 wks‐sustained response respectively. Methods A prospective, single‐centre, phase 2, open‐label, randomized controlled trial (registered at Clinical Trials Registry of India CTRI/2019/08/020501) 73 out of 97 patients with newly diagnosed ITP, initial platelet count <30 x 109/L of any age, were enrolled between March 2019 to July 2021 at AIIMS Rishikesh. Baseline blood counts, biochemistry, and serology were performed on all patients. Bone marrow examination was done in patients>50 years of age. Pts with any prior therapy or secondary cause for thrombocytopenia were excluded. Bleeding severity was graded as per the WHO bleeding score. Pts were randomized by block randomization into group A (grp A) or group B (grp B)(Figure:1). Grp A received Prednisolone at 1mg/kg/day for 4 wks (age >12yrs) and 2mg/kg/day for 2 wks (age < 12yrs) and tapered gradually over 2 months. Grp B received Dexamethasone at 40mg/day for 4 days/cycle (40mg/m2 for 4 days in age <12yrs), for 3 cycles every 14 days. Response was defined as Complete response (CR) plt = 100 x 109 /L. Response (R) plt = 30 x 109/L or > 2‐fold increase in plt from baseline, no bleeding. No response (NR) plt < 30 x 109 /L or <2 fold increase in plt from baseline or bleeding. Loss of response (LR) plt < 30 x 109/L or bleeding, from CR or R previously. Results of the 73 evaluable pts, 34 (47%) were randomized to Grp A and 39 (53%) to Grp B. Median age was 29 (range 3 to 75 yrs), of which 13 (18%) were <12 yrs. 10pts (14%) had no bleeding at presentation, 63pts (86%) presented with bleeding, of which 23pts (45%) had mild bleeding grade 1‐2, 27pts (37%) had moderate bleeding grade 3, and 4 pts had severe bleeding grade 4 including 1pt with intracerebral bleed. 68 out of 73pts (94%) had an initial response at 4 wks, 54pts (74%) attained CR, and 14(20%) had R. 5pts had NR requiring second‐line therapy. Sustained response was assessed at 12 weeks in 58 out of 73 patients, 15 patients were lost to follow‐up. Sustained response (CR plus R) was seen in 39pts (67%). Meanwhile, 15pts (26%) had a loss of response (LR), and 4pts (7%) had no response (NR) (Table 1). 57 (88%) out of 73pts had treatment‐related adverse events (TRAE) and 16 (22%) had no TRAE. Common TRAEs included weight gain, infections, acne, fatigue, hyperglycemia, hypertension, dyspepsia, and insomnia. 1pt had proximal myopathy and 1 had Central Serous Retinopathy. The severity of TRAE was graded as per CTCAE. There was no severe TRAE (CTCAE grade 4 or 5). All the TRAE resolved spontaneously or with treatment (Figure:2) Summary/Conclusion Our study shows comparable results between group A and group B. Both standard dose prednisolone and pulsed high dose dexamethasone are equally efficacious as first‐line therapy in ITP, in terms of initial and sustained response. Both are well tolerated. There was no difference in the incidence of treatment‐related adverse events in either group. Therefore we conclude, that either standard‐dose prednisolone or pulsed high‐dose dexamethasone is a safe and efficacious option as firstline therapy in ITP.
