AB  -  Background‐aim: NETs arise more frequently from GI tract. 177Lu‐PRRT is considered a valid therapeutic option for pts with advanced GI NETs. Many studies were carried out to establish the ideal dosage schedule, able to delivery the right dose to the tumor and to respect healty tissues. Primary aimof this study is to evaluate efficacy and safety of two different 177Lu‐PRRTdosage schedules. Secondary aimis to investigate the presence of prognostic factors for 177Lu‐PRRT efficacy. Methods: The study was prospective, phase II, open label and disease‐oriented. Every 6 to 8 weeks, pts received 177Lu‐DOTATATE at the dosage of either 3.7 GBq (RA) or 5.5 GB(FA)/cycle repeated 5 time, according to presence of risk factors for toxicity, such as previous 90 Y‐PRRT (cumulative activity C 9.25 GBq) serum creatinine ranging from 1.5 to 2 mg/dl, morphological renal abnormalities, severe hypertension, insulin‐dependent diabetes not properly controlled by drugs, previous platinum‐based chemotherapy and age[80 years. Efficacy was assessed in terms of PFS and OS. PFS was defined as the time from treatment beginning to the date of the first documented evidence of PD or death due to any cause. OS was defined as the time from treatment beginning to the time of death from any cause. CT and/or MRI were performed 3, 6, 12, 18, and 24 months after the end of treatment and every 6‐12 months thereafter. Safety was assessed considering the occurrence of renal and/or hematological toxicity according to CTCAE v 3.0. As prognostic factors were tested: the presence of FDG avid lesions (FDG SUVmax C 2.5), the tumor burden score (1: up to 5 lesions in 1 site, 2: multiple lesions in up to 2 sites, 3: multiple lesions in more than 2 sites) and the hepatic involvement (0: no lesions, 1: up to 6 lesions, 2: more than 6 lesions). Results: 43 pts (28 M and 15 F) were evaluable and were monitored for a median period of 67 months (range 12.6‐96.3). All pts had a 68Ga‐dotapeptide PET/CT and/or octreoscan positive scan in documented lesions. 25 Pts received a median full total activity of 25.7 GBq (range 22.2‐27.8 GBq). 18 Pts were treated with a median reduced total activity of 18.4 GBq (range 14.4‐20.4). Median PFS of Pts who received RA was 55.6 months (14.3‐79.6) while median PFS of Pts treated with FA was 52.7 (23.3‐69.0, p = 0.999). Median OS was 82.0 (55.6‐nr) in Pts who received FA and has not been reached in those treated with RA (p = 0.427). 21 pts were FDG negative and in these pts median PFS was 60.1 months (36.8‐nr), 12 pts were FDG positive and among them PFS was 29.8 (9.0‐69.0, p = 0.05). In 19 pts (44.2%) with less than 6 liver metastases, PFS was 55.6 months (18.0‐nr), while in 18 pts (41.9%) with more than 6 lesions was 30.4 months (14.3‐36.8, p = 0.01). PFS and OS did not change significantly according to the tumor burden score. Neither hematological nor renal grade 3‐4 toxicity was noticed in both groups. Conclusions: After 5 years FU, Lu‐PRRT proves to be an effective and safe therapeutic option in advanced GI NET. Important prognostic factors are the presence of FDG avid lesions and hepatic involvement regardless total activity injected.
