AB  -  Background/Purpose: Bimekizumab (BKZ) is a monoclonal IgG1 antibody that selectively inhibits IL‐17F in addition to IL‐17A. In patients with active ankylosing spondylitis (AS), BKZ demonstrated sustained efficacy and tolerability through 156 weeks (wks) in a phase 2b study, and up to 24wks in the phase 3 study BE MOBILE 2. Here we present the efficacy and safety data of BKZ versus placebo (PBO) in patients with active non‐radiographic axial spondyloarthritis (nr‐axSpA) up to Wk24 in the ongoing pivotal phase 3 study, BE MOBILE 1. Methods: BE MOBILE 1 (NCT03928704) comprises a 16‐wk double‐blind, PBO‐controlled period and 36‐wk maintenance period. Patients were aged ≥18 years, had BASDAI ≥4 and spinal pain ≥4 at baseline, and sacroiliitis on MRI and/or elevated CRP at screening. Patients were randomised 1:1 BKZ 160 mg every 4 weeks (Q4W):PBO. From Wk16, all patients received BKZ 160 mg Q4W. Primary and secondary efficacy endpoints were assessed at Wk16, and up to Wk24. Treatment‐emergent adverse events (TEAEs; MedDRA v19.0) are reported among patients who received ≥1 BKZ dose by preferred term up to Wk24. Results: Of 254 randomised patients (BKZ: 128; PBO: 126), 244 (96.1%) completed Wk16, 240 (94.5%) Wk24. Baseline characteristics were comparable between groups: mean age 39.4 years, symptom duration 9.0 years; 45.7% patients were female, 77.6% HLA‐B27+ and 10.6% TNFi‐Inadequate Responders (IR). At Wk16, the primary (Assessment of SpondyloArthritis international Society 40 response, ASAS40: 47.7% BKZ versus 21.4% PBO; p < 0.001) and all ranked secondary endpoints were met (Table). ASAS40 responses at Wk16 were consistent across TNFi‐naïve (46.6% BKZ versus 22.9% PBO) and TNFi‐IR (60.0% BKZ versus 11.8% PBO) populations. Responses were rapid with BKZ, including in PBO patients who switched to BKZ at Wk16, and increased to Wk24 (Table; Figure). At Wk24, >50% of BKZ‐randomised patients achieved Ankylosing Spondylitis Disease Activity Score (ASDAS) <2.1 (Figure). Up to Wk24, 124/244 (50.8%) patients had ≥1 TEAE; most frequent were upper respiratory tract infection (7.0%), nasopharyngitis (6.6%), pharyngitis (2.9%) and oral candidiasis (2.9%). All cases of oral candidiasis were non‐severe and non‐systemic, and none led to treatment discontinuation. Up to Wk24, incidence of serious TEAEs was low (0.4%). No IBD, active tuberculosis, major adverse cardiovascular events, or deaths were reported; incidence of uveitis was low (0.8%). Conclusion: Dual inhibition of IL‐17A and IL‐17F with BKZ in patients with active nr‐axSpA resulted in rapid, clinically relevant improvements in efficacy outcomes versus PBO, including suppression of inflammation. No new safety signals were observed.
