AB  -  INTERVENTION: Intervention 1: 117‐128 subjects with RA or PsA or AS, or nrAxSpA planned to use Mida Rheuma App added to conventional patient management (Mida Rheuma App group); The study will consist of 2 study periods: Screening period: up to 1 week with study visit 1. Observational period: 12 weeks with 2 study visits (Day 1, week 12). Subjects will participate in the study for a maximum of 13 weeks (screening to End of Study (EOS)). Intervention 2: 117‐128 subjects with RA or PsA or AS or nrAxSpA planned to be treated according to conventional patient management only (conventional patient management group); The study will consist of 2 study periods: Screening period: up to 1 week with study visit 1. Observational period: 12 weeks with 2 study visits (Day 1, week 12). Subjects will participate in the study for a maximum of 13 weeks (screening to End of Study (EOS)). CONDITION: L40 ‐ Psoriasis M05 ‐ Seropositive rheumatoid arthritis M06 ‐ Other rheumatoid arthritis M45 ‐ Ankylosing spondylitis M46 ‐ Other inflammatory spondylopathies PRIMARY OUTCOME: To compare the effect of the Mida Rheuma App that is added to conventional patient management on patient’s Quality of Life versus conventional patient management in the treatment of participants. ; Primary endpoint: Change in Mida Rheuma App group from baseline at week 12 versus conventional patient management in Quality of Life, measured through the Short Form Health Survey (SF‐36). INCLUSION CRITERIA: ‐ If using DMARD therapy, subjects are permitted to use any csDMARD or bDMARD, alone or in combination and must have been on a stable dose of the drug for at least 4 weeks prior to Day 1 ‐ If taking systemic or steroids, must have been on a stable dose of the drug for at least 4 weeks prior to Day 1 ‐ If taking non‐steroidal anti‐inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs), these must be at a stable dose for at least 2 weeks prior to Day 1. SECONDARY OUTCOME: 1. The effect of the Mida Rheuma App that is added to conventional patient management on Patient Disease Activity versus conventional patient management in the treatment of participants with RA, PsA or axSpA ; 2. The effect of Mida Rheuma App that is added to conventional patient management on Patient Physical Impairment versus conventional patient management ; 3. The effect of Mida Rheuma App that is added to conventional patient management on Patient‐Reported Outcomes versus conventional patient management ; 4. Adverse events (AE) during the study Major Secondary Efficacy Endpoints: ; Change in Mida Rheuma App group from baseline to Week 12 versus conventional patient management: ; For patients with RA: ; Change from baseline in Rheumatoid Arthritis Disease Activity Index‐5 (RADAI‐5) ; For patients with RA and axSpA who have peripheral joint involvement: ; Change from baseline in Patient Global Assessment of Disease Activity (PtGADA) ; Patient’s Global Assessment of Pain Intensity (PPAIN) ; Change from baseline in Disease Activity Score 28 ‐ CRP (DAS28‐CRP) ; Change from baseline in Disease Activity Score 28 ‐ ESR (DAS28‐ESR) ; Change from baseline in Clinical Disease Activity Inde X(CDAI) ; Change from baseline in Simplified Disease Activity Inde X(SDAI) ; Change from baseline in Morning stiffness (severity and duration) ; For SpA and axPsA patients with spine/ sacroiliac joint (SIJ) involvement: ; Change from baseline in Bath Ankylosing Spondylitis Disease Activity (BASDAI) Major Secondary Efficacy Endpoints: ; Change in Mida Rheuma App group from baseline to Week 12 versus conventional patient management: ; For patients with RA: ; Change from baseline in Rheumatoid Arthritis Disease Activity Index‐5 (RADAI‐5) ; For patients with RA and axSpA who have peripheral joint involvement: ; Change from baseline in Patient Global Assessment of Disease Activity (PtGADA) ; Patient’s Global Assessment of Pain Intensity (PPAIN) ; Change from baseline in Disease Activity Score 28 ‐ CRP (DAS28‐CRP) ; Change from baseline in Disease Activity Scor