AB  -  Introduction: Daratumumab (D) is approved as monotherapy and in combination regimens for multiple myeloma. In the phase 3 MAIA study, D‐Rd vs Rd improved progression‐free survival (PFS) and induced deeper responses (complete response or better [≥CR], 49% vs 27%; minimal residual disease [MRD]‐negativity, 29% vs 9%) in transplant‐ineligible NDMM patients (pts). The median age was 73 yr, and 44% of pts were ≥75 yr. D‐Rd also improved PFS in older pts (≥75 yr). We present a subgroup analysis of pts in MAIA by frailty status. Methods: Pts were randomised 1:1 to 28‐day cycles of Rd (R: 25 or 10mg [based on renal function] PO QD on Days 1‐21; d: 40 or 20mg [based on age <75 yr or BMI] PO/IV on Days 1, 8, 15 and 22)±D (16mg/kg IV) QW for Cycles 1‐2, Q2W for Cycles 3‐6, and Q4W thereafter, until disease progression. Primary endpoint was PFS. Key secondary endpoints included rates of ≥CR and MRD negativity (10∧‐5), and safety. Post hoc analyses were performed by pt frailty status. Frailty assessment was performed retrospectively using age, Charlson Comorbidity Index, and baseline ECOG PS score; pts were classified as fit, intermediate (int), total non‐frail (fit+int), or frail (Facon et al., Leukemia 2019). Results: For all randomised pts (D‐Rd, n=368 and Rd, n=369), frailty scores were calculated retrospectively (frail, 172 [47%] and 169 [46%], respectively; int, 128 [35%] and 122 [33%]; total non‐frail, 196 [53%] and 200 [54%]; fit, 68 [18%] and 78 [21%]). Median relative dose intensity (RDI) of D was similar across subgroups (≥98.0%). Median RDI of R was higher in the total non‐frail vs frail subgroup with D‐Rd (77.2% vs 65.4%) but lower in the total non‐frail vs frail subgroup with Rd (86.4% vs 92.9%). After 36.4‐mo median follow‐up, the PFS benefit of D‐Rd vs Rd was maintained in all subgroups: fit (median, not reached [NR] vs 41.7 mo; hazard ratio [HR] 0.41; 95% confidence interval [CI], 0.22‐0.75), int (NR in both arms; HR 0.53; 95% CI, 0.35‐0.80), total non‐frail (NR vs 41.7 mo; HR 0.48; 95% CI, 0.34‐0.68), and frail (NR vs 30.4 mo; HR 0.62; 95% CI, 0.45‐0.85). Improved rates of ≥CR (fit, 56% vs 22%, P<0.0001; int, 54% vs 25%, P<0.0001; total non‐frail, 55% vs 24%, P<0.0001; frail, 44% vs 31%, P=0.0144), and MRD negativity (fit, 34% vs 8%, P=0.0001; int, 33% vs 9%, P<0.0001; total nonfrail, 33% vs 9%, P<0.0001; frail, 24% vs 10%, P=0.0008) were seen for D‐Rd vs Rd across subgroups. Overall, the most common grade 3/4 treatment‐emergent adverse event (TEAE) was neutropenia (D‐Rd/ Rd: fit, 44%/29%; int, 46%/43%; total non‐frail, 45%/37%; frail, 58%/33%), and the most common serious TEAE was pneumonia (fit, 12%/8%; int, 10%/10%; total non‐frail, 11%/9%; frail, 18%/8%). The frail subgroup had an increased rate of treatment discontinuation due to TEAEs (D‐Rd/Rd: fit, 7%/14%; int, 6%/16%; total non‐frail, 7%/16%; frail, 10%/19%), death (fit, 7%/16%; int, 16%/28%; total non‐frail 13%/23%; frail, 34%/34%), and death due to TEAEs (fit, 1%/4%; int, 5%/3%; total non‐frail, 4%/4%; frail, 12%/12%) vs other subgroups. Additional efficacy and safety data will be presented. Conclusions: Improved efficacy with D‐Rd vs Rd was observed across frailty subgroups, consistent with the overall study population; frail pts had generally poorer outcomes in both arms. The most common grade 3/4 TEAE in all subgroups was neutropenia. These findings support the clinical benefit of D‐Rd in transplant‐ineligible NDMM pts enrolled in MAIA, regardless of frailty status.
