AB  -  Introduction: Without scientific evidences about its benefit, the majority of in vitro fertilization(IVF) settings are routinely requesting patients to take a variable period of bed rest following embryo transfer(ET). This behaviour encourages the belief that refraining from physical activity would help the implantation procedure, consequently elevating stress levels as previously suggested in different papers. In this sense, there is some information available supporting the hypothesis that resting or not will render, at least, comparable result, and also a negative impact has been described in women resting after ET due to the anatomical position of the uterus. Nevertheless, none of these studies have been performed adequately controlling the main factors influencing the results, such as oocyte quality with the use of an ovum donation model. The aim of this prospective, randomized, and controlled trial is to determine whether controlled bed rest following ET influences IVF outcome, as measured by ongoing pregnancy rates, after controlling the adequate randomization of parameters affecting the main outcome measures. Material and Methods: In a prospective, controlled and randomized trial, authorized by the local Institutional Review Board(IRB), from February 2010 until January 20th 2011, a total of 181 patients undergoing IVF‐ET with ovum donation were counselled and explained about the study and their written consents were obtained after acceptance. The inclusion criteria were being free from any uterine major anomaly and aged between 25 and 49 years undergoing oocyte donation, regardless its indication. Couples having severe male factor (<5mill/ml motile sperm) were excluded from the study. Patients were randomized in two groups following a computer‐based randomization list: after the ET, patients from group R (resting, n = 88) were transferred gently from the embryo transfer table to their rooms and requested to remain supine for 10 minutes, as confirmed by the nurse. Patients from group NR (not resting, n = 93) were requested to ambulate immediately after ET. All embryo transfers were performed by the same gynaecologist (SAG). Ongoing pregnancy was confirmed by ultrasound at least 12 weeks later. Statistical analysis was performed using t‐tests to compare means and chi‐square for proportions, with their corresponding 95% within brackets. Results: Randomization effectiveness was confirmed comparing the most relevant variables in NR and R respectively. There were no differences in inseminated oocytes per patient 11.48(10.90‐12.05)vs.11.60(10.97‐12.24), fertilized oocytes 8.63 (8.08‐9.19)vs.8.43(7.88‐8.98), embryos transferred 1.99(1.97‐ 2.01)vs.1.98(1.93‐2.02), frozen embryos 2.66(2.22‐3.10)vs.2.28(1.84‐2.71), waiting list days 14.30(13.09‐15.51)vs 14.65(13.56‐15.74), recipient's age 41.4y(40.53‐42.26)vs.42.18(41.31‐43.06), BMI 21.88(21.18‐22.59) vs.22.49(21.92‐23.06), donor's E2 on the hCG day 2541pg/ml(2289‐2793) vs.2534(2250‐2818), P4 on the hCG day 0.75ng/ml(0.62‐0.87)vs.0.82(0.68‐ 0.97), stimulation length 9.5days(8.7‐10.2)vs.9.9(9.2‐10.6), total gonadotropin doses 2137(2030‐2243)vs.2251(2111‐2391),. The proportion of cycles using vitrified oocytes was also similar: 51.6%(41.4‐61.8)vs.48.3%(37.9‐58.7), as the mean day of embryo transfers 5.04(4.88‐5.20) vs.4.67(4.44‐4.90). Embryo quality parameters on days 2‐3 or blastocyst were also very similar. Pregnancy rates were 77.4%(68.9‐85.9) vs.76.1%(67.2‐85.0), implantation rates 44.25%(36.3253.18)vs.49.46%(41.53‐57.39) and lower miscarriage rates were found in NR 15.1%(6.9‐23.4)vs.27.3%(16.6‐38.0) without reaching statistically significance. Ongoing pregnancy rate (OPR) were not statistically different, although a clear trend to improved OP in NR group is noted 62.4%(52.6‐72.2) vs.48.9%(38.5‐59.3), p = 0.068. Risk ratio was 1.27(0.97‐1.66), OR 1.73(0.95‐3.13), and attributable fraction of the exposure 21.6%(0‐39.9), while number needed to treat was 7.4. Interim analysis results lead us to conclude that the trial must continue. Conclusions: In an oocyte donation model to standardize oocyte quality, there are comparable success rates resting or not after ET, and there is an evident trend to worse results when resting 10 minutes after ET, linked to increased miscarriage rates, compared to immediate ambulation of the patient. Its translation into ongoing pregnancy rates is nearly significant and the trial must be completed before this conclusion can be reached. The anatomical or physical reasons to explain this finding are still unknown.
