AB  -  We have previously shown among 149 members of the Oxford study prospective from diagnosis of non‐insulin‐dependent diabetes under 66 years old between 1973 and 1976, that there is a graded relationship between glycaemic status and the prevalence of retinopathy as judged by fundal colour photographs in 1982. This was so whether the current glycosylated hemoglobin percentage was used, or a mean of the fasting venous plasma glucose levels 1, 3, and 5 years after diagnosis (ie, under treatment) or throughout (adding the initial, pretreatment value for calculation of that mean). The liability to retinopathy in 1982 was also related to the duration of the longest typical symptom before diagnosis, as recounted then, which was itself correlated with the fasting glucose at diagnosis. We now present the results from 106 diabetic patients who had fundal colour photography in both 1982 and 1985. At diagnosis they were 52 ± 10 years old (mean ± SD), with mean values of 28.2 ± 5.2 for Body Mass Index (W/H2), 11.8 ± 4.1 mmol/L for fasting plasma venous glucose (PG), and 0.72 ± 0.24 mmol/L for fasting plasma nonesterified fatty acids (NEFA). 55% were male, and 48% had been randomly allocated to a classic 'low carbohydrate' diet, and the remainder to 'modified fat' dietary advice. By 1982, 34 were still managed by dietary advice alone, while 54 had also been prescribed a sulfonylurea, and 18 insulin. In 1985 only 23 were free of retinopathy (NR) compared to 66 in 1982, while 44 had minimal retinopathy (MR, less than 5 microaneurysms in each fundus) against 19 in 1982.
