AB  -  Background: Axial spondyloarthritis (axSpA) is a chronic, immune‐mediated, inflammatory disease, mainly affecting the sacroiliac joints (SIJ) and spine [1]. Peripheral manifestations (arthritis, enthesitis and dactylitis), and extra‐musculoskeletal manifestations (uveitis, psoriasis and inflammatory bowel disease [IBD]) are also common in patients with axSpA, contributing significantly to the disease burden [2]. Previous cluster analyses based on clinical manifestations identified two axSpA endotypes: patients with predominantly axial disease, hereafter Endotype A, and patients with combined axial disease and peripheral manifestations, hereafter Endotype B [3]. Endotype B has been associated with higher disease activity, reduced quality of life and worse treatment outcomes in two independent real‐world cohorts [3–5]. Bimekizumab (BKZ), a monoclonal IgG1 antibody that selectively inhibits interleukin (IL)‐17F in addition to IL‐17A, has shown sustained efficacy and safety to Week 104 in patients across the full disease spectrum of axSpA in the phase 3 studies BE MOBILE 1 and 2, and to 5 years in the phase 2b BE AGILE study in radiographic (r‐)axSpA [6, 7]. Objectives: To evaluate the differences in efficacy and safety between patients with two clinical endotypes of axSpA upon dual IL‐17A and IL‐17F inhibition with BKZ to Week 52, using a validated clustering algorithm. Methods: The study designs for BE MOBILE 1 (NCT03928704; non‐radiographic [nr‐]axSpA) and BE MOBILE 2 (NCT03928743; r‐axSpA) have been reported previously [8]. Patients were randomised to subcutaneous BKZ 160 mg every 4 weeks (Q4W) or placebo (PBO), with all patients receiving BKZ from Week 16. Patients pooled across BE MOBILE 1 and 2 were categorised into Endotype A (predominantly axial manifestations) and Endotype B (axial and peripheral manifestations) using a validated Classification and Regression Tree (CART) clustering algorithm based on the following baseline characteristics: sex, age at axSpA onset <40 years, disease duration <2 years, HLA‐B27 status and presence of arthritis, enthesitis, dactylitis, uveitis, psoriasis and IBD [3]. This clustering approach has demonstrated prognostic value in identifying patients at risk of poorer outcomes [3–5]. Unlike the published algorithm, buttock pain, triggering infection and NSAID response were not used to determine endotype, as these data were not collected in BE MOBILE 1 and 2. Retention rates and efficacy data are reported to Week 52 for all randomised patients (N=586), stratified by endotype. Efficacy was evaluated using Assessment of SpondyloArthritis international Society 40% (ASAS40) response and Axial Spondyloarthritis Disease Activity Score clinically important improvement (ASDAS‐CII), reported using non‐responder imputation (NRI) and observed case (OC), and ASDAS low disease activity (ASDAS LDA) and ASDAS change from baseline (CfB), reported using multiple imputation (MI). Pooled safety data are reported for patients receiving ≥1 dose of BKZ to Week 52 (N=574), stratified by endotype. Results: Of the 586 patients randomised in BE MOBILE 1 and 2, 402 (68.6%) patients were categorised into Endotype A (PBO: 168; BKZ: 234), and 184 (31.4%) patients were categorised into Endotype B (PBO: 69; BKZ: 115). Baseline characteristics of patients with the two clinical endotypes are presented in the Table 1. Retention rates at Week 52 were similar across endotypes, with a Kaplan‐Meier retention rate of 88.3% in Endotype A and 89.7% in Endotype B. At Week 16, higher ASAS40 response rates were observed with BKZ vs PBO regardless of endotype; these rates continued to increase to Week 52 in patients receiving continuous BKZ (Endotype A: 59.4%; Endotype B: 59.1%; NRI; Figure 1A). Similar patterns of improvement were largely observed for ASDAS‐CII and ASDAS LDA across endotypes (Figure 1B–C). Across endotypes, greater reductions from baseline in ASDAS were observed with BKZ compared with PBO at Week 16. Reductions from baseline in ASDAS continued to Week 52 in patients receiving continuous BKZ and were largely comparable across endotypes (Endotype A: −1.7; Endotype B: −1.9; Figure 1D). When evaluated separately in patients with nr‐axSpA and r‐axSpA, efficacy outcomes across endotypes were largely comparable to the pooled patient population. Across most outcomes at Week 16, responses achieved with PBO in Endotype B were lower than in Endotype A, while the responses achieved with BKZ were largely comparable across endotypes. The safety profile of BKZ was consistent between endotypes (treatment‐emergent adverse events [TEAEs]: Endotype A: 89.1% [352/395], Endotype B: 90.5% [162/179]; serious TEAEs: Endotype A: 12.2% [48/395], Endotype B: 13.4% [24/179]). Discontinuation rates due to TEAEs were low and similar across endotypes (Endotype A: 5.8% [23/395]; Endotype B: 6.1% [11/179]). No deaths occurred in either endotype during the treatment period. Conclusion: BKZ demonstrated comparable retention, efficacy and safety in both endotypes across the full disease spectrum of axSpA through Week 52. These results suggest BKZ may provide effective treatment for patients with axSpA regardless of clinical endotype, potentially addressing an unmet need in patients with a higher frequency of peripheral manifestations. REFERENCES: [1] Navarro‐Compán V. Ann Rheum Dis 2021;80:1511–21. [2] De Winter JJ. Arthritis Res Ther 2016;18:196. [3] Costantino F. Rheumatology 2022;61:3289–98. [4] De Craemer A‐S. Rheumatology 2022;61:3279–88. [5] Costantino F. Arthritis Rheumatol 2016;68:1660–8. [6] Baraliakos X. EULAR 2024 [POS0806]. [7] Deodhar A. EULAR 2024 [POS0215]. [8] Baraliakos X. Ann Rheum Dis 2024;83:199–213. [Figure presented][Figure presented] Acknowledgements: Funded by UCB. Medical writing support provided by Costello Medical and funded by UCB. Disclosure of Interests: Félicie Costantino Speaking honoraria from Amgen, Celltrion, Eli Lilly, Janssen, Novartis and UCB, Consultancy fees from Amgen, Celltrion, Eli Lilly, Janssen, Novartis and UCB, Ann‐Sophie De Craemer Speaker fees from UCB, Filip van den Bosch Speakers bureau fees from AbbVie, Amgen, Janssen, Merck, Novartis, Pfizer and UCB, Consultancy fees from AbbVie, Alfasigma, Amgen, Eli Lilly, Galapagos, Grey Wolf Therapeutics, Janssen, Novartis, Pfizer and UCB, Maxime Breban Consultancy fees from Novartis and UCB, Investigational grants from MSD and Novartis, Vanessa Taieb Shareholder of UCB, Employee of UCB, Diana Voiniciuc Contractor for UCB and employee of Veramed, Natasha de Peyrecave Employee of UCB, Dirk Elewaut Consultancy fees from AbbVie, Eli Lilly, Galapagos, Novartis and UCB, Speaker fees from AbbVie, Eli Lilly, Galapagos, Novartis and UCB, Maria Antonietta D'Agostino Speaking honoraria from AbbVie, Amgen, BMS, Boehringer Ingelheim, Eli Lilly, Galapagos, Janssen, Novartis, Pfizer and UCB, Consultancy fees from AbbVie, Amgen, BMS, Boehringer Ingelheim, Eli Lilly, Galapagos, Janssen, Novartis, Pfizer and UCB. © The Authors 2025. This abstract is an open access article published in Annals of Rheumatic Diseases under the CC BY‐NC‐ND license (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by‐nc‐nd/4.0/). Neither EULAR nor the publisher make any representation as to the accuracy of the content. The authors are solely responsible for the content in their abstract including accuracy of the facts, statements, results, conclusion, citing resources etc.
