DO  -  10.1016/S0168-8278(13)61420-8
AB  -  Background: ALV inhibits cyclophilin A, an essential host protein for HCV replication. We investigated the efficacy and safety of ALV+PR vs ALVplacebo+PR in HCVG1 subjects with previous PR failure. Methods: 461 patients stratified by BMI, IL28B genotype and previous PR response, were randomized to ALV600mg QD+PR (ALV600QD, n = 121); ALV800QD+PR (117); ALV400BID+PR (109); or PR (114), for 48 weeks. 77% Caucasians, mean BL HCVRNA 6.3 log10 IU/mL, 30% HCVG1a, 25% compensated cirrhosis (Cir), 79% CT/TT IL28B genotype, 43% relapser (Rel), 16% partial responder (Par) and 34% null responder (Null), 7% uncharacterized NR. ALV was put on clinical hold because of a few pancreatitis cases on ALV+PR, when patients had received at least 31 weeks of ALV+PR, and completed 48 weeks with PR alone. Results: In overall ITT, ALV+PR had superior SVR12 to PR (p < 0.001) in all groups (45% ALV600QD+PR, 54% ALV800QD+PR, 67% ALV400BID+PR, vs 15% PR). (Table presented) Highest efficacy was among those who received ALV400BID+PR for 40‐48 weeks of treatment with (n = 18) 89% SVR12 ALV400BID+PR, (19) 74% ALV600QD+PR, (20) 75% ALV800QD+PR vs (10) 30% PR. Viral breakthrough on ALV was lowest in ALV400BID+PR (2.8% vs 5.5% with P/R). SAEs in 9.9% ALV+PR vs 5.3% P/R and were most common with ALV400BID+PR (15.7%). 10.5 discontinued ALV+PR therapy vs 5.3% PR. One case of pancreatitis (fully recovered) occurred with ALV+PR. Most common AEs were headache, fatigue, anaemia, neutropenia, nausea and hyperbilirubinemia. The incidence of confirmed hypertension was low, but was more common with ALV. Conclusion: All ALV+PR doses achieved high rates of on treatment viral response and SVR12 despite shorter than planned ALV treatment. The greatest benefit was among Null and Cir vs PR patients. In future, ALV is intended to be developed as IFN free treatment in combination with DAAs.
