DO  -  10.2337/db159321471
AB  -  A pilot randomized clinical trial to assess two different approaches to insulin therapy in type 1 diabetic youth aged <26 years was recently completed in Rwanda. Fifty participants were randomized to basal glargine insulin (G) and later prandial regular insulin (n=26, mean age 18yrs) versus NPH/ regular (N/R) insulin twice daily (N=24, mean age 20yrs). The primary outcome (glycemic control measured by HbA1c) was previously reported as showing no treatment group difference. We now report on a secondary outcome ‐ Diabetes Related Quality of Life (DRQoL) ‐ which was assessed using an extension of the adolescent version of the DCCT DQoL by interviewing, in Kinyarwanda, the surviving 48 participants 6 months after the final clinical visit. There were no significant differences between the two regimens for any individual measures of impact, worry or satisfaction. However, more participants in the NPH/regular insulin group reported hypoglycemia as a problem (92% vs. 29% p<.0001), while glargine was rated as “very convenient” by more participants (83% vs. 46% p=0.007). Glargine users also scored somewhat lower on the impact question as “To how often do you find your diabetes prevents you from participating in school activities?” (p=0.08). Overall these youth appeared to be coping with their diabetes well with 77% saying diabetes never or very seldom interfered with their family life, though 37.5% were embarrassed by having to deal with their diabetes in public. In general, responses were similar to those seen in the U.S., though definitive comparisons are complicated by assessing DRQoL in Sub‐Saharan Africa (SSA) using questions appropriate for the developed world. The lack of a non‐diabetic group for comparison is another major limitation. To our knowledge this is the first time DQoL has been assessed in East African youth and provides encouragement for the development of a SSA specific DQoL instrument.
UR  -  https://www.cochranelibrary.com/central/doi/10.1002/central/CN-01103686/full
