DO  -  10.1016/j.clnesp.2023.09.889
AB  -  Rationale: IBS represents chronic condition where gut ‐ brain axis disruption occurs. Novel treatment approaches are focussed on gut microbiota modulation. Body composition monitoring provides information needed for adequate nutrional support and reveals interesting data in gut microbiota modulation strategies. Methods: We have performed bioimpedance, dynamometry and anthropometric measurements including skinfold thickness evaluation in patients undergoing fecal microbiota transplantation with mixed multi‐donor microbiota obtained from healthy donors. Complex body composition measurements were realized within MISCEAT clinical trial (ClinicalTrials.gov Identifier: NCT04899869) in 28 patients. Bodyweight and height measurement, bioimpedance and dynamometry were performed at baseline, week 5, week 13 and week 32. Medical Body Composition Analyzer Seca mBCA 515 (Seca, Germany) was used to measure changes in body composition (8‐point bioelectric impedance analysis at a frequency of 5–50 kHz with a current of 100 μA), scanning performed with threepairs of hand electrodes and two pairs of leg electrodes, measurements performed with light clothing and without metal objects (jewellery, keys). The weight was determined in patients wearing underwear using the Seca mBCA 515. The height was determined by a standardised technique with a metal stadiometer with an accuracy of 1 mm. Detailed anthropometry was realized by nutritional therapists. It involved weight, height, abdominal (waist) circumference, arm and thigh circumference and skinfolds (biceps, triceps, subscapular, suprailiacal). Skinfolds were assessed using Harpenden Skinfold Caliper. Results: Results obtained reveal body composition data in patients with IBS ‐ D a IBS ‐ M undergoing fecal microbiota transplantation within the MICEAT clinical trial. Blinded data are presented due to the ongoing status of the clinical trial. Conclusion: Body composition assessments including bioimpedance and anthropometric measurements along with dynamometry play important role in IBS patient nutrition care management. References: Hurych J, Vejmelka J, Hlinakova L, Kramna L, Larionov V, Kulich M, Cinek O, Kohout P. Protocol for faecal microbiota transplantation in irritable bowel syndrome: the MISCEAT study ‐ a randomised, double‐blind cross‐over study using mixed microbiota from healthy donors. BMJ Open. 2022 Jun 27;12(6):e056594. doi: 10.1136/bmjopen‐2021‐056594. PMID: 35760542; PMCID: PMC9237876. Acknowledgement to all the study team performing MISCEAT trial. Supported by Ministry of Health of the Czech Republic, grant nr. NV19‐01‐00127. All rights reserved. Disclosure of Interest: None declared
