AB  -  Background: Axial spondyloarthritis (axSpA) is a chronic rheumatic disease requiring optimal management. Assessment of SpondyloArthritis international Society ≥40% improvement (ASAS40) and ASAS partial remission (ASAS PR) are stringent outcomes in trials, while in clinical practice the focus is on sustained remission (inactive disease [ID]) or low disease activity (LDA) according to axSpA Disease Activity Score (ASDAS; <1.3 and <2.1, respectively). Maintenance of response is an internationally recommended target for patient care.[1] Bimekizumab (BKZ) is a monoclonal IgG1 antibody that selectively inhibits interleukin (IL)‐17F in addition to IL‐17A. BKZ demonstrated sustained clinical efficacy to Week 52 in patients across the full disease spectrum of axSpA in the phase 3 studies BE MOBILE 1 and 2.[2] Objectives: To assess the maintenance of response to BKZ over 2 years in the open‐label extension (OLE) of those studies. Methods: BE MOBILE 1 (NCT03928704) and 2 (NCT03928743) comprised a 16‐week double‐blind period followed by a 36‐week maintenance period in patients with non‐radiographic (nr‐) and radiographic (r‐)axSpA, respectively.[2] Patients were randomised to receive subcutaneous BKZ 160 mg every 4 weeks (Q4W) or placebo (PBO); from Week 16, all received BKZ. At Week 52, eligible patients could enrol into BE MOVING (OLE; NCT04436640). The proportions of patients achieving ASAS40, ASAS PR, ASDAS LDA and ASDAS ID to Week 104 were assessed among BKZ‑randomised patients who achieved each respective outcome at Week 16, pooled across studies. Presented data use non‐responder imputation (NRI), multiple imputation (MI) and worst category imputation (WCI; ASDAS only). Observed case (OC) data are also reported. Treatment‐emergent adverse events (TEAEs) to Week 104 are reported for patients who received ≥1 BKZ dose, including patients who switched from PBO to BKZ at Week 16. Results: A total of 128 and 221 patients were randomised to BKZ in BE MOBILE 1 and 2, respectively (N=349). High proportions of patients who achieved a response at Week 16 maintained their responses at Week 104 (Figure 1). At Week 16, 160 (45.8%) patients achieved ASAS40; this increased to 180 (51.6%) patients at Week 104 (NRI). Of patients who achieved ASAS40 at Week 16, 85.7% maintained this response at Week 104 (MI). At Week 16, ASAS PR was achieved by 86 (24.6%) patients; this increased to 100 (28.7%) patients at Week 104 (NRI). Of patients who achieved ASAS PR at Week 16, 76.8% also achieved this outcome at Week 104 (MI; Figure 1). ASDAS LDA was achieved by 152 (43.6%) patients at Week 16; this increased to 172 (49.3%) at Week 104 (NRI). Of patients who achieved ASDAS LDA at Week 16, 89.3% also achieved this outcome at Week 104 (MI). ASDAS ID was achieved by 58 (16.6%) patients at Week 16; this increased to 88 (25.2%) at Week 104 (NRI). Of patients who achieved ASDAS ID at Week 16, 76.0% achieved this outcome at Week 104 (MI; Figure 1). Through Week 104, 514/574 (89.5%; exposure‐adjusted incidence rate per 100 patient‐years [EAIR/100 PY]: 141.9) patients had ≥1 TEAE whilst receiving BKZ; 72 (12.5%; EAIR/100 PY: 5.4) had serious TEAEs. 39 (6.8%; EAIR/100 PY: 2.8) patients discontinued BKZ due to TEAEs. Conclusion: Using the most critical statistical methodology (NRI or WCI; MI), BKZ maintained stringent clinical responses from Week 16 to Week 104 in axSpA. No new safety signals were observed. REFERENCES: [1] Ramiro S. Ann Rheum Dis 2023;82:19–34. [2] Baraliakos X. Ann Rheum Dis. 2024;83:199–213. [Figure presented] Acknowledgements: Funded by UCB. Editorial support provided by Costello Medical and funded by UCB. Disclosure of Interests: Fabian Proft Speakers bureau for AbbVie, Amgen, BMS, Celgene, Galapagos, Hexal, Janssen, Medscape, MSD, Novartis, Pfizer, Roche and UCB, Consultancy fees for AbbVie, Amgen, BMS, Celgene, Galapagos, Hexal, Janssen, Medscape, MSD, Novartis, Pfizer, Roche and UCB, Grant/research support from Eli Lilly, Novartis and UCB, Désirée van der Heijde Associate Editor for Annals Rheumatic Diseases; editorial board member for Journal of Rheumatology and RMD Open; advisor for Assessment Axial Spondyloarthritis international Society; Director of Imaging Rheumatology BV, Consultant for AbbVie, ArgenX, BMS, Eli Lilly, Galapagos, GSK, Janssen, Novartis, Pfizer, Takeda, and UCB, Sergio Schwartzman Medical board member at National Psoriasis Foundation, Speakers bureau for AbbVie, Eli Lilly, Janssen, Pfizer, UCB, Consulting fees from Abbvie, Eli Lilly, Janssen, UCB, UpToDate, Teijin, Grant support from Eli Lilly, Joerg Ermann Consulting fees from Abbvie, Janssen, Novartis, and Pfizer, Grant support from Novartis and Pfizer, Alexander Marten Employee of UCB, Ute Massow Employee of UCB, George Stojan Employee of UCB, Vanessa Taieb Shareholder of UCB, Employee of UCB, Diana Voiniciuc Contractor for UCB and employee of Veramed, Astrid van Tubergen Consultant for Novartis, Pfizer and UCB; Speakers bureau for Pfizer, Grant/research support from MSD, Novartis, Pfizer and UCB, Victoria Navarro‐Compán Speakers bureau for AbbVie, Eli Lilly, Fresenius Kabi, Janssen, MSD, Novartis, Pfizer, and UCB, Consultancy fees from AbbVie, Eli Lilly, Galapagos, MoonLake, MSD, Novartis, Pfizer, and UCB, Grant/research support from AbbVie and Novartis, Xenofon Baraliakos Paid instructor for AbbVie, BMS, Chugai, Eli Lilly, Galapagos, MSD, Novartis, Pfizer, and UCB, Speakers bureau from AbbVie, BMS, Chugai, Eli Lilly, Galapagos, MSD, Novartis, Pfizer, and UCB, Consultancy fees from AbbVie, BMS, Chugai, Eli Lilly, Galapagos, Gilead, Novartis, Pfizer, and UCB, Grant/research support from AbbVie, Celltrion, Janssen and Novartis. © The Authors 2025. This abstract is an open access article published in Annals of Rheumatic Diseases under the CC BY‐NC‐ND license (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by‐nc‐nd/4.0/). Neither EULAR nor the publisher make any representation as to the accuracy of the content. The authors are solely responsible for the content in their abstract including accuracy of the facts, statements, results, conclusion, citing resources etc.
