DO  -  10.1111/jsr.14291
AB  -  Introduction: The Psychomotor Vigilance Test (PVT) detects objective measures of reduced alertness with high sensitivity in acute and chronic sleep deprivation. Various questionnaires, such as the Functional Outcomes of Sleep Questionnaire (FOSQ) or the Epworth Sleepiness Scale (ESS), are used to evaluate subjective vigilance and sleepiness. Our study aimed to evaluate if subjective measures predict objective measures of reduced vigilance in obstructive sleep apnea (OSA). Method: OSA patients (post‐hoc analysis of the randomized trial EudraCT: 2017‐004767‐13), n = 52, 28.3% females, age 62.5 ± 9.8 years, body mass index (BMI) 27.8 ± 3.3 kg/m2, apneahypopnea index (AHI) 50.9 ± 22.3 events/hours, ESS 11.9 ± 3.8, ESS at least six by inclusion criteria) underwent a polysomnography (PSG) study and two PVT assessments, one on the evening prior to the PSG (ePVT), as well as one on the following morning (mPVT). PVT response speed is calculated as 1/reaction time. We analysed the predictive capabilities of FOSQ vigilance subscale and the ESS total score for PVT performance by using the likelihood ratio test (LR) from nested linear regression models adjusted for age, sex, and PSG derived AHI. Results: PVT reaction speed was slightly lower during evening compared to morning PVT (ePVT 3.03 ± 0.37, mPVT 2.98 ± 0.36, p < 0.05). The FOSQ vigilance subscale but not the ESS total score significantly improved the prediction model for PVT performance both for the morning (pFOSQ = 0.0106, LRFOSQ = 0.00747) and the evening PVT (pFOSQ = 0.0145, LRFOSQ = 0.00972). The results are adjusted for age, sex, and AHI. Conclusion: In patients with moderate to severe OSA, our study identified that outcomes from the FOSQ vigilance subscale appear to be a better predictor for PVT response speed when compared with the outcomes of the ESS total score. Both scales appear to assess different components of cognitive impairment in OSA. Conflict of Interest: Yes‐ The clinical trial was sponsored by Desitin GMBH, Hamburg, Germany. DF, KRJ, ESA, JH and DZ are completely or partially funded by EU Horizon 2020 grant Nr. 965417 Sleep Revolution. DF, KRJ, DZ, CS report no COI. ESA reports honoraria from Nox Medical, ResMed, Jazz Pharmaceuticals, Linde Healthcare, Wink Sleep, Apnimed, Vistor and is member of the Philips Medical Advisory Board. JH reports lectures for SomnoMed. LG report lectures for Resmed, Philips, Astra Zeneca, Lundbeck, Itamar. JH LG and JH are shareholders in a company with a patent for pharmacological treatment in sleep apnea licensed to Desitin.
